ce)\n|\n|-\n| ''[[Larry King Live]]''\n| Herself\n| 2 episodes\n|\n|-\n| 2006\u20132008\n| ''[[The Emperor's New School]]''\n| 36 episodes\n| Yzma (voice)\n| * '''Won''': [[Annie Award]] for Voice Acting in a Television Production (2007\u20132008)\n* '''Won''': [[Daytime Emmy Award for Outstanding Performer In An Animated Program]] (2007\u20132008)\n|-\n| 2007\n| ''[[American Dad!]]''\n| \"Dope and Faith\"\n| Fortune Teller (voice)\n|\n|-\n| 2009\n| ''[[Wonder Pets!]]''\n| \"Save the Cool Cat and the Hip Hippo/Tuck and Buck\"\n| Cool Cat (voice)\n|\n* '''Won''': [[Daytime Emmy Award for Outstanding Performer In An Animated Program]]\n|-\n| 2010\n| ''[[The Simpsons]]''\n| \"[[Once Upon a Time in Springfield]]\"\n| Herself (voice)\n| Aired posthumously\n|}\n\n===Documentary===\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! Year\n! Film\n! Role\n|-\n| 1982\n| ''All by Myself: The Eartha Kitt Story'' <small>(Documentary)</small>\n| Herself\n|-\n| 1995\n| ''[[Unzipped (film)|Unzipped]]'' <small>(Documentary)</small>\n| Herself\n|-\n| rowspan=\"2\"| 2002\n| ''The Making and Meaning of We Are Family'' <small>(Documentary)</small>\n| Herself\n|-\n| ''The Sweatbox'' <small>(Documentary)</small>\n| Herself\n|}\n\n===Stage work===\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! Year\n! Title\n! Location\n! Role\n! Notes\n|-\n| rowspan=\"2\"|1945\n| ''[[Katherine Dunham#Dancer and choreographer|Blue Holiday]]''\n| [[Broadway theatre|Broadway]]\n| Performer\n| as a member of the [[Katherine Dunham Company|Katherine Dunham Troupe]]; a short-lived production at the [[Belasco Theatre]]<ref name=\"KathyDunhamCongress\">{{cite web|url=http://lcweb2.loc.gov/diglib/ihas/html/dunham/dunham-timeline.html|title=Selections from the Katherine Dunham Collection|publisher=[[Library of Congress]]|accessdate=December 14, 2014}}</ref>\n|-\n| ''[[Katherine Dunham#Dancer and choreographer|Carib Song]]''\n| Broadway\n| Company\n| as a member of the Katherine Dunham Troupe; performed at the [[Adelphi Theatre (New York City)|Adelphi Theatre]] as an Original Broadway production<ref name=\"KathyDunhamCongress\"/>\n|-\n| rowspan=\"2\"|1946\n| ''[[Katherine Dunham#Dancer and choreographer|Bal N\u00e8gre]]''\n| Broadway, and Europe\n| Performer\n| as a member of the Katherine Dunham Troupe; widely acclaimed Concert at the Belasco Theatre<ref name=\"KathyDunhamCongress\"/>\n|-\n| unknown\n| [[Mexico]]\n| Performer\n| performed successfully as a member of the Katherine Dunham Troupe which was under contract with Teatro Americano for more than two months at the request of [[Doris Duke]]<ref name=\"KathyDunhamCongress\"/>\n|-\n| 1948\n| ''[[Katherine Dunham#Dancer and choreographer|Caribbean Rhapsody]]''\n| [[West End theatre|West End]], and Paris\n| [[Chorus girl]]\n|as a member of the Katherine Dunham Troupe; performed at the [[Prince of Wales Theatre]] (West End) and [[Th\u00e9\u00e2tre des Champs-\u00c9lys\u00e9es]] (Paris)<ref name=\"ThatBadEarthaCredits\">{{cite AV media notes|others=Eartha Kitt|title=[[That Bad Eartha]] [[That Bad Eartha#That Bad Eartha (EP) (1954)|10\" Long Play (United Kingdom Version)]]|year=1955|type= sleeve note|publisher=[[His Master's Voice]]|id=}}</ref><ref name=\"KathyDunhamCongress\"/>\n|-\n| 1949-50\n| unknown\n| Paris\n| Herself,<br />Performer\n| first solo show / leading performance; performed at Carroll's Niterie; is where [[Orson Welles]] discovered her<ref name=\"ThatBadEarthaCredits\" /><ref>{{cite AV media notes|others=Eartha Kitt|title=[[Eartha Kitt discography#Studio albums|Down to Eartha]] (United Kingdom Version)|year=1955|type= sleeve note|publisher=[[His Master's Voice]]|id=}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://flashbak.com/eartha-kitt-and-orson-welles-in-paris-in-1950-22597/|title=Eartha Kitt and Orson Welles in Paris in 1950|author=Baker, Rob|publisher=Alum Media Ltd.|date=October 16, 2014|accessdate=December 14, 2014}}</ref>\n|-\n| rowspan=\"2\"|1950\n| ''Time Runs''\n| Paris<ref name=telegraph />\n| rowspan=\"3\"|[[Helen of Troy]]\n| rowspan=\"2\"|In segment based on ''[[Faust: The Second Part of the Tragedy|Faust]]''; performed \"Hungry Little Trouble\" written by [[Duke Ellington]]; cast by Orson Welles<ref name=\"ThatBadEarthaCredits\" />\n|-\n| ''An Evening With Orson Welles''\n| [[Frankfurt]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.stripes.com/news/eartha-kitt-wins-raves-in-welles-show-at-frankfurt-1.16046|title=Eartha Kitt wins raves in Welles' show at Frankfurt|author=Fanning, Win|date=August 13, 1950|work=[[Stars and Stripes (newspaper)|Stars and Stripes]]|accessdate=December 14, 2014}}</ref>\n|-\n| 1951\n| ''[[The Tragical History of Doctor Faustus|Dr. Faustus]]''\n| Paris\n| with Orson Welles\n|-\n| 1952\n| ''[[New Faces of 1952]]''\n| Broadway\n| Polynesian girl,<br />Featured dancer,<br />Featured singer\n|\n|-\n| 1954\n| ''Mrs. Patterson''\n| Broadway\n| Theodora (Teddy) Hicks\n| Original Broadway production\n|-\n| 1957\n| ''[[Shinbone Alley]]''\n| Broadway\n| Mehitabel\n| Original Broadway production\n|-\n| 1959\n| ''Jolly's Progress''\n| Broadway\n| Jolly Rivers\n|\n|-\n| 1965\n| ''[[The Owl and the Pussycat (film)|The Owl and the Pussycat]]''\n| U.S. National tour\n| Performer\n|\n|-\n| 1967\n| ''Peg''\n| Regional (US)\n|\n|\n|-\n| 1970\n| ''The High Bid''\n| London\n| Performer\n|\n|-\n| 1972\n| ''Bunny''\n| London\n| Performer\n|\n|-\n| 1974\n| ''Bread and Beans and Things''\n| [[Earl Carroll Theatre|Aquarius Theater]]<ref>''Los Angeles Herald-Examiner'' and ''Los Angeles Times''. June 8, 1974. {{full citation needed|date=June 2018}}</ref>\n| Performer\n|\n|-\n| 1976\n| ''A Musical Jubilee''\n| U.S. National tour\n| Performer\n|\n|-\n| 1978\n| ''[[Timbuktu!]]''\n| Broadway\n| Shaleem-La-Lume\n|\n* '''Nominated''': [[Tony Award for Best Actress in a Musical]]\n|-\n| 1980\n| ''Cowboy and the Legend''\n| Regional (US)\n| Performer\n|\n|-\n| 1982\n| ''[[New Faces of 1952]]'' (Revival)\n| [[Off-off-Broadway]]\n| Polynesian girl<br />Featured dancer<br />Featured singer\n|\n|-\n| 1985\n| ''[[Blues in the Night (musical)|Blues in the Night]]''\n| U.S. National tour\n| Performer\n|\n|-\n| 1987\n| ''[[Follies]]'' (London Revival)\n| London\n| Carlotta Campion\n| Replacement for [[Dolores Gray]]\n|-\n| 1989\n| ''Aladdin''\n| [[Palace Theatre, Manchester]]\n| Performer\n|\n|-\n| 1989\n| ''Eartha Kitt in Concert''\n| London\n| Performer\n|\n|-\n| 1994\n| ''Yes''\n| Edinburgh\n| Performer\n|\n|-\n| 1995\n| ''Sam's Song''\n| [[Unitarian Church of All Souls]]\n| Performer\n| Benefit concert\n|-\n| 1996\n| ''Lady Day at Emerson's Bar and Grill''\n| Chicago\n| Performer\n|\n|-\n| 1998\n| ''[[The Wizard of Oz (1987 musical)|The Wizard of Oz]]'' (return engagement) [[off-Broadway]]\n| U.S. National tour\n| The Wicked Witch\n|\n|-\n| rowspan=\"2\"|2000\n| ''[[The Wild Party (LaChiusa musical)|The Wild Party]]''\n| Broadway\n| Delores\n| Original Broadway production\n* '''Nominated''': [[Tony Award for Best Featured Actress in a Musical]]\n* '''Nominated''': [[Drama Desk Award for Outstanding Featured Actress in a Musical]]\n|-\n| ''[[Cinderella (Rodgers and Hammerstein musical)|Cinderella]]''\n| [[Madison Square Garden]], and U.S. National tour\n| Fairy Godmother\n|\n|-\n| 2003\n| ''[[Nine (musical)|Nine]]''\n| Broadway\n| Liliane La Fleur\n| Replacement for [[Chita Rivera]]\n|-\n| 2004\n| ''[[Cinderella]]'' ([[New York City Opera]] revival)\n| [[David H. Koch Theater]]\n| Fairy Godmother\n|\n|-\n| 2006\n| ''[[Mimi le Duck]]''\n| [[Off-off-Broadway]]\n| Madame Vallet\n|\n|-\n| 2007\n| ''[[All About Us (musical)|All About Us]]''\n| [[Westport Country Playhouse]]\n| Performer\n|\n|}\n\n===Video games===\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! Year\n! Title\n! Role\n! Notes\n|-\n| 2000\n| ''[[The Emperor's New Groove (video game)|The Emperor's New Groove]]''\n| Yzma\n| voice role\n|-\n|}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|30em}}\n\n==Further reading==\n* Gent, Helen (May 4, 2009). [https://web.archive.org/web/20110203141654/http://au.lifestyle.yahoo.com/marie-claire/features/life-stories/article/-/5870362/eartha-kitt-the-feline-femme-fatale/ \"Eartha Kitt: The Feline Femme Fatale\"]. ''[[Marie Claire]]'' (Australia).\n*{{Cite book|last=Kitt|first=Eartha|title=Alone with Me : A New Autobiography|year=1976|publisher=H. Regnery|isbn=0-8092-8351-4|location=Chicago|oclc=1945260}}\n* Walsh, David (December 27, 2008). [http://wsws.org/articles/2008/dec2008/pers-d27.shtml \"Harold Pinter and Eartha Kitt, artists and opponents of imperialist war\"]. World Socialist Web Site.\n\n==External links==\n{{commons category|Eartha Kitt}}\n* {{official|http://www.earthakitt.com/}}\n* {{Discogs artist|Eartha Kitt}}\n* {{IMDb name|457755}}\n* {{IBDB name}}\n* {{iobdb name|33251}}\n* {{EmmyTVLegends name|eartha-kitt}}\n* [http://www.tvguide.com/celebrities/eartha-kitt/148312 Eartha Kitt] at [[TV Guide]]\n* {{Find a Grave|32398636}}\n\n===Video / audio footage===\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20070213122217/http://openvault.wgbh.org/saybrother/MLA000985/index.html \"An Evening with Eartha Kitt\"]. ''[[Basic Black|Say Brother]]''. [[WGBH-TV]]. September 14, 1979.\n* [https://www.npr.org/templates/story/story.php?storyId=98713115 \"Singer And Actress Eartha Kitt Dies\"]. ''[[All Things Considered]]''. NPR. December 25, 2008.\n* [https://www.npr.org/templates/story/story.php?storyId=98737624 \"Eartha Kitt on Piano Jazz\"]. ''Piano Jazz''. NPR. May 1, 2009 (recorded February 12, 1993).\n* [http://www.visionaryproject.org/kitteartha \"Eartha Kitt\"]. National Visionary Leadership Project.\n\n{{S-start}}\n!colspan=\"3\" style=\"background:#C1D8FF;\"| [[Batman (TV series)|''Batman'' role]]\n|-\n{{succession box\n| before = [[Julie Newmar]]\n| title = [[Catwoman|Catwoman actress]]\n| years = 1967\u20131968\n| after = [[Michelle Pfeiffer]]\n}}\n{{s-end}}\n\n{{Eartha Kitt}}\n{{Navboxes\n| title = Awards for Eartha Kitt\n| list =\n{{Annie Award for Voice Acting in a Feature Production}}\n{{Daytime Emmy Award Outstanding Performer In An Animated Program}}\n}}\n\n{{Portal bar|Biography|Music}}\n\n