Added content)", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Eartha_Kitt"}
{"title_page": "Disappearance of Robert Levinson", "text_new": "{{Redirect|Robert Levinson|the American lyricist|Robert Levenson}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name          = Robert Levinson\n| image         = Robert-Levinson.png\n| alt           = \n| caption       = Levinson while in captivity, November 2010\n| birth_name    = Robert Alan Levinson\n| birth_date    = {{Birth date|1948|03|10}}<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.interpol.int/How-we-work/Notices/View-Yellow-Notices#2008-30703|title=INTERPOL|work=interpol.int}}</ref>\n| birth_place   = [[Flushing, New York|Flushing]], [[New York (state)|New York]], U.S.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.fbi.gov/wanted/kidnap/robert-a-levinson|title=ROBERT A. LEVINSON|website=Federal Bureau of Investigation}}</ref>\n| death_date    = \n| death_place   = [[Iran]]\n| disappeared_date   = {{Disappeared date and age|2007|03|09|1948|03|10}} \n| disappeared_place  = [[Kish Island]], [[Iran]]\n| disappeared_status =[[Declared death in absentia|Declared dead ''in absentia'']]<br />{{death date and age|2020|3|25|1948|3|10}}<ref name=\"dead\"/>\n| nationality   = [[Americans|American]]\n| other_names   = \n| occupation    = Federal agent\n| years_active  = \n| known_for     = Disappearance in Iran\n| notable_works = \n}}\n'''Robert Alan Levinson''' (March 10, 1948 \u2013 date of death before March 25, 2020) was an American former [[Drug Enforcement Administration]] and [[Federal Bureau of Investigation]] agent who disappeared on March 9, 2007, in [[Kish Island]], [[Iran]] while on a mission for the CIA. He is believed to have been held captive by the [[government of Iran]].<ref>{{cite news| url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/world/national-security/ex-fbi-agent-who-went-missing-in-iran-was-on-rogue-mission-for-cia/2013/12/12/f5de6084-637b-11e3-a373-0f9f2d1c2b61_story_1.html | work=[[The Washington Post]] | first=Adam | last=Goldman | title=National Security | date=December 13, 2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite news | title = Intrigue Surrounds Former FBI Agent Who Disappeared in Iran Two Months Ago | url = http://legacy.utsandiego.com/news/nation/20070510-1037-iran-missing.html | newspaper = San Diego Union-Tribune | author = Pat Milton | agency = Associated Press | date = 2007-05-10 | accessdate = 2013-01-08 | archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20131202222233/http://legacy.utsandiego.com/news/nation/20070510-1037-iran-missing.html | archive-date = 2013-12-02 | url-status =}}</ref> On November 26, 2013, Levinson, if he was still alive, became the longest-held American in history, surpassing [[Terry A. Anderson]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2013/dec/12/robert-levinson-fbi-cia-iran-missing|title=Former FBI agent missing in Iran was working for the CIA \u2013 report|last=Ackerman|first=Spencer|date=2013-12-13|work=The Guardian|access-date=2019-11-16|language=en-GB|issn=0261-3077}}</ref> According to his family, he suffered from [[type 1 diabetes]], [[gout]], and [[hypertension]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://video.foxnews.com/v/2214047211001/son-of-captured-american-pleads-for-fathers-release/|title=Son of captured American pleads for father's release|work=Fox News}}</ref>  His passport has never shown up in any other country.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://articles.dailypress.com/2007-09-30/news/0709290237_1_iranian-president-mahmoud-ahmadinejad-william-and-mary-americans-hostage |title=Family Asks For Help Locating Man Possibly Missing In Iran|work= [[Daily Press (Virginia)|Daily Press]]|date= September 30, 2007}}</ref>  On March 25, 2020, Levinson's family announced his death, and although the date is unknown, it is assumed that he died while in Iranian custody.\n\n==Disappearance==\nU.S. officials believed Levinson had been arrested by Iranian intelligence officials to be interrogated and used as a bargaining chip in negotiations with Washington, but as every lead fizzled out and Iran repeatedly denied any involvement in his disappearance, many in the U.S. government believed Levinson was probably dead.<ref name=\"family\">{{cite news|title = Missing ex-FBI agent Robert Levinson in hostage video: 'Help me' | url = http://www.csmonitor.com/USA/Latest-News-Wires/2011/1209/Missing-ex-FBI-agent-Robert-Levinson-in-hostage-video-Help-me-Video | agency = Associated Press | date = 2011-12-09}}</ref> He was last seen alive in photographs from April 2011, wearing an orange jumpsuit and holding signs, apparently asking for help in broken English.<ref name=Alive />\n\nOn December 12, 2013, the [[Associated Press]] (AP) reported that their investigations revealed that Levinson indeed had been working for the [[Central Intelligence Agency]] (CIA), contradicting the U.S. government's statement that he was not an employee of the government at the time of his capture, U.S. officials had publicly insisted that Levinson went to Iran as a private investigator, working a cigarette smuggling case.<ref>{{Citation|title=White House: Robert Levinson not a government employee|agency=BBC|date=December 13, 2013|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/world-us-canada-25373010|accessdate=December 13, 2013|work=BBC News}}</ref> AP had first confirmed Levinson's CIA ties in 2010.<ref>{{Citation|title=Missing American in Iran was working for CIA|agency=Associated Press|date=December 12, 2013|url=http://www.politico.com/story/2013/12/robert-levinson-cia-missing-iran-101107.html|accessdate=December 12, 2013}}</ref><ref name=\"RT-American-who\">{{cite web|url=http://on.rt.com/ci6oh7|title=American who vanished in Iran was on unsanctioned CIA mission \u2013 report|work=rt.com}}</ref><ref name=\"auto\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2013/12/14/world/middleeast/a-disappearing-american-spy-and-the-cia.html|title=A Disappearing Spy, and a Scandal at the C.I.A.|first=Barry|last=Meier|date=December 13, 2013|via=NYTimes.com}}</ref> He was on an unauthorized intelligence-gathering mission about the Iranian government for the U.S. government. When his case came to light inside the U.S. government, it produced a serious scandal.<ref name=\"auto\" /> Levinson's travel was planned by three CIA officials who did not follow the proper vetting process or seek the necessary approval for the mission from their supervisors. Kish Island in the Persian Gulf is a free-trade zone, meaning Americans do not need a visa to enter, a tourist destination and stronghold of international [[organized crime]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.spiegel.de/politik/ausland/robert-levinson-war-fuer-die-cia-in-iran-und-wurde-2007-entfuehrt-a-938799.html|title=Fall Robert Levinson: In Iran vermisster US-B\u00fcrger arbeitete f\u00fcr CIA|date=December 13, 2013|via=Spiegel Online}}</ref> In 2008 the CIA forced the CIA officials to turn in early resignations and disciplined seven others after an internal investigation determined they were responsible for sending Levinson on the mission to Iran. Levinson's source on Kish was [[Dawud Salahuddin]], an American fugitive accused of the killing of the prominent former Iranian diplomat [[Ali Akbar Tabatabaei]] in 1980. The exiled Tabatabaei was holding meetings of a counter-revolutionary group at his US home at the time.<ref>{{cite news |last= Mackey |first= Robert |title= Just Another American Hit Man, Actor and Journalist Living in Iran |url= http://thelede.blogs.nytimes.com/2009/09/16/just-another-american-hit-man-actor-and-journalist-living-in-iran |access-date=17 February 2013 |newspaper= The New York Times |date=16 September 2009}}</ref>\n\nWhat Levinson wanted in that mission remains altogether unclear. Levinson had retired from the FBI in 1998 and had become self-employed as a private investigator; his specialty was Russian organized crime gangs, and he was even interviewed numerous times for television documentaries to discuss the topic. Both Levinson and the CIA analyst who hired him, Anne Jablonski, specialized in Russian organized crime and not Iranian issues.<ref name=\"nyt13dec\">{{cite news |url= https://www.nytimes.com/2013/12/14/world/middleeast/a-disappearing-american-spy-and-the-cia.html |title=A Disappearing Spy, and a scandal at the C.I.A. - nytimes.com |newspaper= New York Times |date= December 13, 2013 }}</ref>\n\nIn an interview, Iranian President [[Hassan Rouhani]] spoke of cooperation regarding Levinson's case. \"We are willing to help, and all the intelligence services in the region can come together to gather information about him to find his whereabouts.\"<ref name=\"cnn12dec\">{{cite news |url= http://edition.cnn.com/2013/09/28/us/iran-detained-americans/index.html |title=U.S. official: Obama, Rouhani discussed fate of three Americans - CNN.com |publisher= Edition.cnn.com |date= September 28, 2013 |access-date=2013-12-12}}</ref>\n\n== Alleged Iranian involvement ==\n[[File:Robert Levinson kidnapped.jpg|thumb|right|Robert \"Bob\" Levinson in a 2011 hostage photo.]]\nOn April 4, 2007, a little over three weeks after Levinson was arrested, an article by Iranian state-run [[PressTV]] stated that he \"has been in the hands of Iranian security forces since the early hours of March 9\" and \"authorities are well on the way to finishing the procedural arrangements that could see him freed in a matter of days\". The same article explained that it was established that Levinson's trip to Kish \"was purely that of a private businessman looking to make contact with persons who could help him make representations to official Iranian bodies responsible for suppressing trade in pirated products which is a major concern of his company\".<ref name=\"PressTV\">{{cite news | title = Ex-FBI man in Iran not \"missing\" at all | url = http://edition.presstv.ir/detail/4832.html | publisher = PressTV | date = 2007-04-04 | access-date = 2013-03-24 | archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20131206225353/http://edition.presstv.ir/detail/4832.html | archive-date = 2013-12-06 | url-status = dead }}</ref>\n\nOn January 8, 2013, the Associated Press reported that \"the consensus now among some U.S. officials involved in the case is that despite years of denials, Iran's intelligence service was almost certainly behind the 54-second video and five photographs of Levinson that were emailed anonymously to his family. 'The tradecraft used to send those items was too good, indicating professional spies were behind them', the officials said&nbsp;... While everything dealing with Iran is murky, their conclusion is based on the U.S. government's best intelligence analysis.\"<ref name = \"AP\">{{cite news | title = US sees Iran behind hostage photos of ex-FBI agent | url = http://bigstory.ap.org/article/us-sees-iran-behind-hostage-photos-ex-fbi-agent| publisher = PAP | date = 2013-01-09}}</ref>\n\n== Family investigation ==\nMedia reported in August 2007 that Christine Levinson, wife of Robert, was planning a trip to Iran with their oldest son, Dan. The [[United States Department of State]] stressed that there was a travel warning to that country and they would be doing so at their own risk.<ref name = \"IHT\">{{cite news | title = U.S. woman plans trip to Iran to search for missing former FBI agent husband | url = http://www.iht.com/articles/ap/2007/08/02/america/NA-GEN-US-Iran-Missing-Man.php | newspaper = International Herald Tribune | date = 2007-08-02}}</ref> Iran announced on September 23, 2007, that they would be allowed to visit the country.<ref>{{cite news |title=Iran: Missing American's family can visit |url=http://edition.cnn.com/2007/WORLD/meast/09/23/iran.levinson/ |work=[[CNN]] |date=September 23, 2007 |accessdate=2008-08-08}}</ref>\n\nIn December 2007, Christine and Dan traveled to Iran to attempt to learn more about Levinson's disappearance. They met with Iranian officials in Tehran and traveled to Robert's hotel on Kish, the Hotel Maryam.<ref>{{cite news |title=In Iran, Search for American Yields Little  |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2007/12/24/world/middleeast/24iran.html |work=New York Times |date=December 24, 2007 |first=Nazila |last=Fathi}}</ref> Airport officials allowed Christine and Dan to view the flight manifests for all flights leaving Kish during the time Robert was due to leave, but his name did not appear on any of the lists provided. They were also able to view Robert's signature from the hotel check-out bill on March 9. Iranian officials promised to provide an investigative report to the family, but have yet to do so.<ref>{{cite news |first=Daniel |last=Levinson |title=Missing a Father in Iran |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/wp-dyn/content/article/2008/06/20/AR2008062002274.html |work=[[The Washington Post]] |page=B07 |date=June 22, 2008 |accessdate=2008-08-08}}</ref> In July 2008 and subsequent interviews, Christine and Dan said they wanted to travel to Iran again soon.<ref>{{cite news |title=Wife of ex-FBI agent to repeat Iran visit in search of her husband  |url=http://www.payvand.com/news/08/jul/1147.html |work=Payvand |date=July 15, 2008 |accessdate=2008-08-08}}</ref>\n\n== President Ahmadinejad's statements ==\nPressed by [[Charlie Rose]] in an interview for ''[[CBS This Morning]]'' in September 2012, then-[[Iranian President]] [[Mahmoud Ahmadinejad]] \"did not deny Iran still has Levinson in its custody, and hinted that there had been talks about a prisoner exchange\". Rose asked, \"Is there anything that could happen, a trade or something, that could allow him to come back to the United States?\" Ahmadinejad responded:\n\n<blockquote>I remember that last year Iranian and American intelligence groups had a meeting, but I haven't followed up on it. I thought they'd come to some kind of an agreement.</blockquote>\n\nCBS' John Miller says that \"tacit admission that he's in their custody and that there have been talks\", in and of itself, \"is a big step\".<ref name = \"CBS This Morning\">{{cite news | title = Mahmoud Ahmadinejad drops clue about Robert Levinson, ex-FBI agent who vanished 5 years ago in Iran | url = http://www.cbsnews.com/8301-505263_162-57519554/mahmoud-ahmadinejad-drops-clue-about-robert-levinson-ex-fbi-agent-who-vanished-5-years-ago-in-iran/ | publisher = CBS News | date = 2012-09-25}}</ref>\n\nIn a 2008 interview with [[NBC]]'s [[Brian Williams]], Ahmadinejad was questioned regarding Levinson's case and its status. He responded:\n\n<blockquote>There was a claim made some time ago, some people came over, the gentleman's family came over. They talked and met with our officials and were given our responses. I see no reason for a person who was given an Iranian visa and \u2014 came into Iran, arrived in Iran through official channels, to have problems here. Our security officials and agents have expressed their willingness to assist the FBI, if the FBI has any information about his travels around the world.\n\nWe have said that we are ready to help, to assist with that matter. There are certain informations that only the FBI at the moment has. I am not an expert in that field, as you might appreciate, so I'm not going to make a judgment here whether that information, as they say, is true and only held by the FBI or other parties for that matter.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.nbcnews.com/id/25887437 |title=Transcript: 'Response ... will be a positive one' |accessdate=2008-08-08 |date=July 28, 2008 |format=[[NBC Nightly News]] |work=NBC News}}</ref></blockquote>\n\n== U.S. government investigation ==\n[[File:President Barack Obama meets with Christine Levinson in the Oval Office on March 6, 2012.jpg|thumb|left|President [[Barack Obama]] meets with Christine Levinson in the [[Oval Office]] on March 6, 2012]]\n\nIn June 2007, President [[George W. Bush]] released a statement on Levinson's case, saying: \"I am ... disturbed by the Iranian regime's refusal so far to provide any information on Robert Levinson, despite repeated U.S. requests. I call on Iran's leaders to tell us what they know about his whereabouts.\"<ref>{{cite news | url=http://articles.cnn.com/2007-12-22/world/iran.levinson_1_robert-levinson-christine-levinson-iranian-officials?_s=PM:WORLD | archive-url=https://archive.today/20130410171705/http://articles.cnn.com/2007-12-22/world/iran.levinson_1_robert-levinson-christine-levinson-iranian-officials?_s=PM:WORLD | url-status=dead | archive-date=April 10, 2013 | work=CNN | title=No 'miracle' for American missing in Iran | date=December 22, 2007 }}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=https://georgewbush-whitehouse.archives.gov/news/releases/2007/06/20070601-10.html|title=Statement by the President on Detention of American Citizens by the Iranian Regime|work=The White House|date=June 1, 2007}}</ref>\n\nOn January 13, 2009, U.S. Senator [[Bill Nelson]] revealed during [[Hillary Clinton]]'s confirmation hearing that he believes Robert Levinson is being held in a secret prison in Iran. \"The door has been closed at every turn,\" Nelson said during Clinton's confirmation hearing. \"We think he is being held by the government of Iran in a secret prison.\"<ref>{{cite news| url=http://www.foxnews.com/story/0,2933,479842,00.html | work=Fox News | title=Senator Says Former FBI Agent Who Vanished in 2007 Is in Secret Iran Prison | date=January 13, 2009}}</ref>\n\nAccording to ''[[The New York Times]]'', Levinson had been meeting with [[Dawud Salahuddin]], (an American convert to Islam wanted for the 1980 murder of an Iranian dissident in the US) \"just before he went missing\".<ref name=\"hitman\">{{cite web|url=http://thelede.blogs.nytimes.com/2009/09/16/just-another-american-hit-man-actor-and-journalist-living-in-iran/?hp |title=Just Another American Hit Man, Actor and Journalist Living in Iran|first= Robert |last=Mackey|date= September 16, 2009}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.reuters.com/article/topNews/idUSBLA33261120070413|title=Former FBI agent held in Iran: report|work=Reuters}}</ref>\n\nOn March 8, 2013, the [[Obama administration]] released a statement to mark the sixth anniversary of Levinson's disappearance. Press Secretary Jay Carney said, \n<blockquote>Finding him remains a high priority for the United States, and we will continue to do all that we can to bring him home safely to his friends and family, so they may begin to heal after so many years of extraordinary grief and uncertainty.\n\nThe Iranian Government previously offered assistance in locating Mr. Levinson and we look forward to receiving this assistance, even as we disagree on other key issues.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.whitehouse.gov/the-press-office/2013/03/08/statement-press-secretary-robert-levinson|title=Statement by the Press Secretary on Robert Levinson|work=The White House}}</ref></blockquote>\n\nSecretary of State [[John Kerry]] also met with Levinson's wife and son \"to reiterate that the U.S. government remains committed to locating Mr. Levinson and reuniting him safely with his family\".<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.reuters.com/article/2013/03/08/us-iran-kerry-levinson-idUSBRE9271B020130308|title=John Kerry meets with family of ex-FBI agent missing in Iran|work=Reuters}}</ref>\n\n== Reward ==\n[[File:Robert Levinson Reward.pdf|thumb|right|$20 million reward poster to help find Robert Levinson.]]\nOn March 6, 2012, approaching the fifth anniversary of Robert Levinson's captivity, the [[Federal Bureau of Investigation]] offered a $1-million reward for information leading to his safe recovery and return. In addition, a campaign was launched, using billboards, radio messages, flyers, and a telephone hotline to publicize this reward and obtain information of his whereabouts.<ref name=\"$1 Million Reward Offered for Missing Retired FBI Agent\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.fbi.gov/news/stories/2012/march/levinson/levinson |title=FBI \u2014 $1 Million Reward Offered for Missing Retired Agent |publisher=Fbi.gov |date= |access-date=2012-03-07}}</ref> In conjunction with this announced reward, the [[Society of Former Special Agents of the Federal Bureau of Investigation]] announced that it was giving the two youngest Levinson children $5,000 each to help with their college costs.<ref name=\"$1 Million Reward Offered for Missing Retired FBI Agent\" />\n\nOn March 9, 2015, the FBI increased the reward to up to $5 million for information regarding Levinson's whereabouts.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.fbi.gov/washingtondc/press-releases/2015/eight-year-anniversary-of-the-disappearance-of-robert-a.-levinson?utm_campaign|title=FBI \u2014 Eight Year Anniversary of the Disappearance of Robert A. Levinson|work=FBI}}</ref>\n\nOn November 4, 2019, the [[United States Department of State]] [[Rewards for Justice Program]] offered a $20 million reward for information leading to Levinson's whereabouts.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.fbi.gov/contact-us/field-offices/washingtondc/news/press-releases/fbi-washington-field-office-statement-on-robert-a-levinson-and-the-department-of-state-rewards-for-justice-announcement|title=FBI Washington Field Office Statement on Robert A. Levinson and the Department of State Rewards for Justice Announcement \u2014 FBI|website=www.fbi.gov}}</ref>\n\n== Proof of life ==\nAccording to the [[Associated Press]], Levinson's family received \"irrefutable proof\" of life late in 2010.<ref>{{cite web|author=ADAM GOLDMAN and MATT APUZZO Associated Press |url=http://abcnews.go.com/US/wireStory?id=13049751 |title=Years After Vanishing in Iran, US Man Proven Alive - ABC News |publisher=Abcnews.go.com |date=2011-03-03 |accessdate=2011-12-09}}</ref>  On December 9, 2011, the family released a hostage video they received in November 2010. In the video, Robert appears to have lost considerable weight, and repeatedly pleads for help in returning home.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.politico.com/news/stories/1211/70183.html |title=Robert Levinson, missing ex-FBI agent in hostage video: 'Help me' |work=[[Associated Press]]|date= December 9, 2011}}</ref>\n\nOn January 8, 2013, Levinson's family released photos to the media showing the former agent in an orange jumpsuit with overgrown and unkempt hair. A family spokesman told CNN the photographs were received in April 2011.  CNN reported: \"Asked why the family is releasing the images now, more than 18 months later, the spokesman said: 'The family is anxious that not enough is being done. There is frustration with the lack of progress on the case.'\"<ref name=Alive>{{cite news|url=http://www.cnn.com/2013/01/08/us/iran-missing-fbi-agent/index.html |title=Family releases photos of captive American |publisher=CNN.com |date=2013-01-10 |accessdate=2013-12-12}}</ref>\n\n== President Rouhani's statements ==\nIn an interview with CNN's [[Christiane Amanpour]] during his trip to the United Nations General Assembly in September 2013, Iranian President [[Hassan Rouhani]] spoke of cooperation regarding Levinson's case. \"We are willing to help, and all the intelligence services in the region can come together to gather information about him to find his whereabouts\", Rouhani told Amanpour, \"and we're willing to cooperate on that\".<ref name=\"cnn12dec\" />\n\nIn a subsequent interview with [[Charlie Rose]], Rouhani said, \"As to where his whereabouts when he disappeared, I personally have no information on those details, but naturally when someone disappears their family is suffering in specific.  Everyone must help.  It's natural that everyone must help\".<ref>{{Cite AV media |url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=pJaasDOpHsI |title=Charlie Rose asks Rouhani about Robert Levinson |publisher=YouTube |date=Sep 27, 2013 |author=mwolda |accessdate=2013-12-12 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130927154554/http://www.youtube.com/watch?v=pJaasDOpHsI |archivedate=2013-09-27 }}</ref>\n\n== President Obama's discussion of case with Rouhani ==\nDuring the Obama\u2013Rouhani phone call on September 27, 2013, the first communication between the presidents of the two countries in 34 years, President Obama noted his concern about Levinson's disappearance to Rouhani, and expressed his interest in seeing him reunited with his family.<ref name=\"cnn12dec\" />\n\n== United States Senate resolution ==\nOn May 11, 2015, the [[United States Senate]] voted on [[concurrent resolution]] 16 for the release of Robert Levinson, which passed in a unanimous decision without amendment.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/politics/congress/senate-passes-resolution-for-release-of-americans-in-iran/2015/05/11/fad52814-f82d-11e4-a47c-e56f4db884ed_story.html|title=Senate Passes Resolution for Release of Americans in Iran|author= Deb Riechmann|date=11 May 2015|publisher=|via=washingtonpost.com|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150528230412/http://www.washingtonpost.com/politics/congress/senate-passes-resolution-for-release-of-americans-in-iran/2015/05/11/fad52814-f82d-11e4-a47c-e56f4db884ed_story.html|archivedate=May 28, 2015}}</ref> This resolution states that it is U.S. policy that: (1) the government of the Islamic Republic of Iran should immediately release [[Saeed Abedini]], [[Amir Hekmati]], and [[Jason Rezaian]], and cooperate with the U.S. government to locate and return Robert Levinson; and (2) the U.S. government should undertake every effort using every diplomatic tool at its disposal to secure their release.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.congress.gov/bill/114th-congress/senate-concurrent-resolution/16|title=S.Con.Res.16 - 114th Congress (2015-2016): A concurrent resolution stating the policy of the United States regarding the release of United States citizens in Iran.|first=Risch|last=James|date=20 May 2015|website=www.congress.gov}}</ref>\n\n== Reported death ==\nIn March 2020, it was reported that Levinson's family and the United States government had concluded that it was likely that Levinson had died in Iranian custody before 2020.<ref name=\"dead\">{{Cite news |last=Goldman |first=Adam |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2020/03/25/us/politics/robert-levinson-cia-iran.html |title=Ex-F.B.I. Agent Who Vanished on C.I.A. Mission to Iran Is Likely Dead, U.S. Concludes |date=March 25, 2020 |work=The New York Times |access-date=March 25, 2020 |url-status=live |language=en-US |issn=0362-4331}}</ref>\n\n== See also ==\n{{portal|Biography|Iran|United States}}\n*[[List of people who disappeared mysteriously]]\n*[[List of foreign nationals detained in Iran]]\n{{clear}}\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*[https://www.facebook.com/helpboblevinson/ Help Bob Levinson] on [[Facebook]]\n*[http://helpboblevinson.spaces.live.com/ Help Bob Levinson]\n*[https://www.fbi.gov/wanted/kidnap/robert-a-levinson Bob Levinson wanted poster] [[FBI|FBI web site]], retrieved November 2019.\n\n{{Authority control}}\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Levinson, Robert}}\n\n[[Category:Drug Enforcement Administration agents]]\n[[Category:Federal Bureau of Investigation agents]]\n[[Category:American people taken hostage]]\n[[Category:Missing people]]\n[[Category:People of the Central Intelligence Agency]]\n[[Category:Iran\u2013United States relations]]\n[[Category:1948 births]]\n[[Category:Kidnappings in Iran]]\n[[Category:2000s missing person cases]]\n[[Category:CIA operatives in Iran]]\n[[Category:Date of death unknown]]\n[[Category:People from Flushing, Queens]]\n[[Category:People declared dead in absentia]]\n", "text_old": "{{Redirect|Robert Levinson|the American lyricist|Robert Levenson}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name          = Robert Levinson\n| image         = Robert-Levinson.png\n| alt           = \n| caption       = Levinson while in captivity, November 2010\n| birth_name    = Robert Alan Levinson\n| birth_date    = {{Birth date|1948|03|10}}<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.interpol.int/How-we-work/Notices/View-Yellow-Notices#2008-30703|title=INTERPOL|work=interpol.int}}</ref>\n| birth_place   = [[Flushing, New York|Flushing]], [[New York (state)|New York]], U.S.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.fbi.gov/wanted/kidnap/robert-a-levinson|title=ROBERT A. LEVINSON|website=Federal Bureau of Investigation}}</ref>\n| death_date    = \n| death_place   = [[Iran]]\n| disappeared_date   = {{Disappeared date and age|2007|03|09|1948|03|10}} \n| disappeared_place  = [[Kish Island]], [[Iran]]\n| disappeared_status =[[Declared death in absentia|Declared dead ''in absentia'']]<br />{{death date and age|2020|3|25|1948|3|10}}<ref name=\"dead\"/>\n| nationality   = [[Americans|American]]\n| other_names   = \n| occupation    = Federal agent\n| years_active  = \n| known_for     = Disappearance in Iran\n| notable_works = \n}}\n'''Robert Alan Levinson''' (March 10, 1948 \u2013 date of death before March 25, 2020) was an American former [[Drug Enforcement Administration]] and [[Federal Bureau of Investigation]] agent who disappeared on March 9, 2007, in [[Kish Island]], [[Iran]] while on a mission for the CIA. Levinson's family received $2.5 million annuity from the CIA in order to stop a lawsuit revealing details of his work in Iran and to forestall any revelation of details regarding the arrangement between Levinson and the agency.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://apnews.com/ee9eb08ce68c4f6ab6dba43da5cc398d|title=Iran calls ex-FBI agent's case a 'missing person' file|date=November 11, 2019|website=AP NEWS}}</ref> He is believed to have been held captive by the [[government of Iran]].<ref>{{cite news| url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/world/national-security/ex-fbi-agent-who-went-missing-in-iran-was-on-rogue-mission-for-cia/2013/12/12/f5de6084-637b-11e3-a373-0f9f2d1c2b61_story_1.html | work=[[The Washington Post]] | first=Adam | last=Goldman | title=National Security | date=December 13, 2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite news | title = Intrigue Surrounds Former FBI Agent Who Disappeared in Iran Two Months Ago | url = http://legacy.utsandiego.com/news/nation/20070510-1037-iran-missing.html | newspaper = San Diego Union-Tribune | author = Pat Milton | agency = Associated Press | date = 2007-05-10 | accessdate = 2013-01-08 | archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20131202222233/http://legacy.utsandiego.com/news/nation/20070510-1037-iran-missing.html | archive-date = 2013-12-02 | url-status =}}</ref> On November 26, 2013, Levinson, if he was still alive, became the longest-held American in history, surpassing [[Terry A. Anderson]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2013/dec/12/robert-levinson-fbi-cia-iran-missing|title=Former FBI agent missing in Iran was working for the CIA \u2013 report|last=Ackerman|first=Spencer|date=2013-12-13|work=The Guardian|access-date=2019-11-16|language=en-GB|issn=0261-3077}}</ref> According to his family, he suffered from [[type 1 diabetes]], [[gout]], and [[hypertension]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://video.foxnews.com/v/2214047211001/son-of-captured-american-pleads-for-fathers-release/|title=Son of captured American pleads for father's release|work=Fox News}}</ref>  His passport has never shown up in any other country.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://articles.dailypress.com/2007-09-30/news/0709290237_1_iranian-president-mahmoud-ahmadinejad-william-and-mary-americans-hostage |title=Family Asks For Help Locating Man Possibly Missing In Iran|work= [[Daily Press (Virginia)|Daily Press]]|date= September 30, 2007}}</ref>  On March 25, 2020, Levinson's family announced his death, and although the date is unknown, it is assumed that he died while in Iranian custody.\n\n==Disappearance==\nU.S. officials believed Levinson had been arrested by Iranian intelligence officials to be interrogated and used as a bargaining chip in negotiations with Washington, but as every lead fizzled out and Iran repeatedly denied any involvement in his disappearance, many in the U.S. government believed Levinson was probably dead.<ref name=\"family\">{{cite news|title = Missing ex-FBI agent Robert Levinson in hostage video: 'Help me' | url = http://www.csmonitor.com/USA/Latest-News-Wires/2011/1209/Missing-ex-FBI-agent-Robert-Levinson-in-hostage-video-Help-me-Video | agency = Associated Press | date = 2011-12-09}}</ref> He was last seen alive in photographs from April 2011, wearing an orange jumpsuit and holding signs, apparently asking for help in broken English.<ref name=Alive />\n\nOn December 12, 2013, the [[Associated Press]] (AP) reported that their investigations revealed that Levinson indeed had been working for the [[Central Intelligence Agency]] (CIA), contradicting the U.S. government's statement that he was not an employee of the government at the time of his capture, U.S. officials had publicly insisted that Levinson went to Iran as a private investigator, working a cigarette smuggling case.<ref>{{Citation|title=White House: Robert Levinson not a government employee|agency=BBC|date=December 13, 2013|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/world-us-canada-25373010|accessdate=December 13, 2013|work=BBC News}}</ref> AP had first confirmed Levinson's CIA ties in 2010.<ref>{{Citation|title=Missing American in Iran was working for CIA|agency=Associated Press|date=December 12, 2013|url=http://www.politico.com/story/2013/12/robert-levinson-cia-missing-iran-101107.html|accessdate=December 12, 2013}}</ref><ref name=\"RT-American-who\">{{cite web|url=http://on.rt.com/ci6oh7|title=American who vanished in Iran was on unsanctioned CIA mission \u2013 report|work=rt.com}}</ref><ref name=\"auto\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2013/12/14/world/middleeast/a-disappearing-american-spy-and-the-cia.html|title=A Disappearing Spy, and a Scandal at the C.I.A.|first=Barry|last=Meier|date=December 13, 2013|via=NYTimes.com}}</ref> He was on an unauthorized intelligence-gathering mission about the Iranian government for the U.S. government. When his case came to light inside the U.S. government, it produced a serious scandal.<ref name=\"auto\" /> Levinson's travel was planned by three CIA officials who did not follow the proper vetting process or seek the necessary approval for the mission from their supervisors. Kish Island in the Persian Gulf is a free-trade zone, meaning Americans do not need a visa to enter, a tourist destination and stronghold of international [[organized crime]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.spiegel.de/politik/ausland/robert-levinson-war-fuer-die-cia-in-iran-und-wurde-2007-entfuehrt-a-938799.html|title=Fall Robert Levinson: In Iran vermisster US-B\u00fcrger arbeitete f\u00fcr CIA|date=December 13, 2013|via=Spiegel Online}}</ref> In 2008 the CIA forced the CIA officials to turn in early resignations and disciplined seven others after an internal investigation determined they were responsible for sending Levinson on the mission to Iran. Levinson's source on Kish was [[Dawud Salahuddin]], an American fugitive accused of the killing of the prominent former Iranian diplomat [[Ali Akbar Tabatabaei]] in 1980. The exiled Tabatabaei was holding meetings of a counter-revolutionary group at his US home at the time.<ref>{{cite news |last= Mackey |first= Robert |title= Just Another American Hit Man, Actor and Journalist Living in Iran |url= http://thelede.blogs.nytimes.com/2009/09/16/just-another-american-hit-man-actor-and-journalist-living-in-iran |access-date=17 February 2013 |newspaper= The New York Times |date=16 September 2009}}</ref>\n\nWhat Levinson wanted in that mission remains altogether unclear. Levinson had retired from the FBI in 1998 and had become self-employed as a private investigator; his specialty was Russian organized crime gangs, and he was even interviewed numerous times for television documentaries to discuss the topic. Both Levinson and the CIA analyst who hired him, Anne Jablonski, specialized in Russian organized crime and not Iranian issues.<ref name=\"nyt13dec\">{{cite news |url= https://www.nytimes.com/2013/12/14/world/middleeast/a-disappearing-american-spy-and-the-cia.html |title=A Disappearing Spy, and a scandal at the C.I.A. - nytimes.com |newspaper= New York Times |date= December 13, 2013 }}</ref>\n\nIn an interview, Iranian President [[Hassan Rouhani]] spoke of cooperation regarding Levinson's case. \"We are willing to help, and all the intelligence services in the region can come together to gather information about him to find his whereabouts.\"<ref name=\"cnn12dec\">{{cite news |url= http://edition.cnn.com/2013/09/28/us/iran-detained-americans/index.html |title=U.S. official: Obama, Rouhani discussed fate of three Americans - CNN.com |publisher= Edition.cnn.com |date= September 28, 2013 |access-date=2013-12-12}}</ref>\n\n== Alleged Iranian involvement ==\n[[File:Robert Levinson kidnapped.jpg|thumb|right|Robert \"Bob\" Levinson in a 2011 hostage photo.]]\nOn April 4, 2007, a little over three weeks after Levinson was arrested, an article by Iranian state-run [[PressTV]] stated that he \"has been in the hands of Iranian security forces since the early hours of March 9\" and \"authorities are well on the way to finishing the procedural arrangements that could see him freed in a matter of days\". The same article explained that it was established that Levinson's trip to Kish \"was purely that of a private businessman looking to make contact with persons who could help him make representations to official Iranian bodies responsible for suppressing trade in pirated products which is a major concern of his company\".<ref name=\"PressTV\">{{cite news | title = Ex-FBI man in Iran not \"missing\" at all | url = http://edition.presstv.ir/detail/4832.html | publisher = PressTV | date = 2007-04-04 | access-date = 2013-03-24 | archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20131206225353/http://edition.presstv.ir/detail/4832.html | archive-date = 2013-12-06 | url-status = dead }}</ref>\n\nOn January 8, 2013, the Associated Press reported that \"the consensus now among some U.S. officials involved in the case is that despite years of denials, Iran's intelligence service was almost certainly behind the 54-second video and five photographs of Levinson that were emailed anonymously to his family. 'The tradecraft used to send those items was too good, indicating professional spies were behind them', the officials said&nbsp;... While everything dealing with Iran is murky, their conclusion is based on the U.S. government's best intelligence analysis.\"<ref name = \"AP\">{{cite news | title = US sees Iran behind hostage photos of ex-FBI agent | url = http://bigstory.ap.org/article/us-sees-iran-behind-hostage-photos-ex-fbi-agent| publisher = PAP | date = 2013-01-09}}</ref>\n\n== Family investigation ==\nMedia reported in August 2007 that Christine Levinson, wife of Robert, was planning a trip to Iran with their oldest son, Dan. The [[United States Department of State]] stressed that there was a travel warning to that country and they would be doing so at their own risk.<ref name = \"IHT\">{{cite news | title = U.S. woman plans trip to Iran to search for missing former FBI agent husband | url = http://www.iht.com/articles/ap/2007/08/02/america/NA-GEN-US-Iran-Missing-Man.php | newspaper = International Herald Tribune | date = 2007-08-02}}</ref> Iran announced on September 23, 2007, that they would be allowed to visit the country.<ref>{{cite news |title=Iran: Missing American's family can visit |url=http://edition.cnn.com/2007/WORLD/meast/09/23/iran.levinson/ |work=[[CNN]] |date=September 23, 2007 |accessdate=2008-08-08}}</ref>\n\nIn December 2007, Christine and Dan traveled to Iran to attempt to learn more about Levinson's disappearance. They met with Iranian officials in Tehran and traveled to Robert's hotel on Kish, the Hotel Maryam.<ref>{{cite news |title=In Iran, Search for American Yields Little  |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2007/12/24/world/middleeast/24iran.html |work=New York Times |date=December 24, 2007 |first=Nazila |last=Fathi}}</ref> Airport officials allowed Christine and Dan to view the flight manifests for all flights leaving Kish during the time Robert was due to leave, but his name did not appear on any of the lists provided. They were also able to view Robert's signature from the hotel check-out bill on March 9. Iranian officials promised to provide an investigative report to the family, but have yet to do so.<ref>{{cite news |first=Daniel |last=Levinson |title=Missing a Father in Iran |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/wp-dyn/content/article/2008/06/20/AR2008062002274.html |work=[[The Washington Post]] |page=B07 |date=June 22, 2008 |accessdate=2008-08-08}}</ref> In July 2008 and subsequent interviews, Christine and Dan said they wanted to travel to Iran again soon.<ref>{{cite news |title=Wife of ex-FBI agent to repeat Iran visit in search of her husband  |url=http://www.payvand.com/news/08/jul/1147.html |work=Payvand |date=July 15, 2008 |accessdate=2008-08-08}}</ref>\n\n== President Ahmadinejad's statements ==\nPressed by [[Charlie Rose]] in an interview for ''[[CBS This Morning]]'' in September 2012, then-[[Iranian President]] [[Mahmoud Ahmadinejad]] \"did not deny Iran still has Levinson in its custody, and hinted that there had been talks about a prisoner exchange\". Rose asked, \"Is there anything that could happen, a trade or something, that could allow him to come back to the United States?\" Ahmadinejad responded:\n\n<blockquote>I remember that last year Iranian and American intelligence groups had a meeting, but I haven't followed up on it. I thought they'd come to some kind of an agreement.</blockquote>\n\nCBS' John Miller says that \"tacit admission that he's in their custody and that there have been talks\", in and of itself, \"is a big step\".<ref name = \"CBS This Morning\">{{cite news | title = Mahmoud Ahmadinejad drops clue about Robert Levinson, ex-FBI agent who vanished 5 years ago in Iran | url = http://www.cbsnews.com/8301-505263_162-57519554/mahmoud-ahmadinejad-drops-clue-about-robert-levinson-ex-fbi-agent-who-vanished-5-years-ago-in-iran/ | publisher = CBS News | date = 2012-09-25}}</ref>\n\nIn a 2008 interview with [[NBC]]'s [[Brian Williams]], Ahmadinejad was questioned regarding Levinson's case and its status. He responded:\n\n<blockquote>There was a claim made some time ago, some people came over, the gentleman's family came over. They talked and met with our officials and were given our responses. I see no reason for a person who was given an Iranian visa and \u2014 came into Iran, arrived in Iran through official channels, to have problems here. Our security officials and agents have expressed their willingness to assist the FBI, if the FBI has any information about his travels around the world.\n\nWe have said that we are ready to help, to assist with that matter. There are certain informations that only the FBI at the moment has. I am not an expert in that field, as you might appreciate, so I'm not going to make a judgment here whether that information, as they say, is true and only held by the FBI or other parties for that matter.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.nbcnews.com/id/25887437 |title=Transcript: 'Response ... will be a positive one' |accessdate=2008-08-08 |date=July 28, 2008 |format=[[NBC Nightly News]] |work=NBC News}}</ref></blockquote>\n\n== U.S. government investigation ==\n[[File:President Barack Obama meets with Christine Levinson in the Oval Office on March 6, 2012.jpg|thumb|left|President [[Barack Obama]] meets with Christine Levinson in the [[Oval Office]] on March 6, 2012]]\n\nIn June 2007, President [[George W. Bush]] released a statement on Levinson's case, saying: \"I am ... disturbed by the Iranian regime's refusal so far to provide any information on Robert Levinson, despite repeated U.S. requests. I call on Iran's leaders to tell us what they know about his whereabouts.\"<ref>{{cite news | url=http://articles.cnn.com/2007-12-22/world/iran.levinson_1_robert-levinson-christine-levinson-iranian-officials?_s=PM:WORLD | archive-url=https://archive.today/20130410171705/http://articles.cnn.com/2007-12-22/world/iran.levinson_1_robert-levinson-christine-levinson-iranian-officials?_s=PM:WORLD | url-status=dead | archive-date=April 10, 2013 | work=CNN | title=No 'miracle' for American missing in Iran | date=December 22, 2007 }}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=https://georgewbush-whitehouse.archives.gov/news/releases/2007/06/20070601-10.html|title=Statement by the President on Detention of American Citizens by the Iranian Regime|work=The White House|date=June 1, 2007}}</ref>\n\nOn January 13, 2009, U.S. Senator [[Bill Nelson]] revealed during [[Hillary Clinton]]'s confirmation hearing that he believes Robert Levinson is being held in a secret prison in Iran. \"The door has been closed at every turn,\" Nelson said during Clinton's confirmation hearing. \"We think he is being held by the government of Iran in a secret prison.\"<ref>{{cite news| url=http://www.foxnews.com/story/0,2933,479842,00.html | work=Fox News | title=Senator Says Former FBI Agent Who Vanished in 2007 Is in Secret Iran Prison | date=January 13, 2009}}</ref>\n\nAccording to ''[[The New York Times]]'', Levinson had been meeting with [[Dawud Salahuddin]], (an American convert to Islam wanted for the 1980 murder of an Iranian dissident in the US) \"just before he went missing\".<ref name=\"hitman\">{{cite web|url=http://thelede.blogs.nytimes.com/2009/09/16/just-another-american-hit-man-actor-and-journalist-living-in-iran/?hp |title=Just Another American Hit Man, Actor and Journalist Living in Iran|first= Robert |last=Mackey|date= September 16, 2009}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.reuters.com/article/topNews/idUSBLA33261120070413|title=Former FBI agent held in Iran: report|work=Reuters}}</ref>\n\nOn March 8, 2013, the [[Obama administration]] released a statement to mark the sixth anniversary of Levinson's disappearance. Press Secretary Jay Carney said, \n<blockquote>Finding him remains a high priority for the United States, and we will continue to do all that we can to bring him home safely to his friends and family, so they may begin to heal after so many years of extraordinary grief and uncertainty.\n\nThe Iranian Government previously offered assistance in locating Mr. Levinson and we look forward to receiving this assistance, even as we disagree on other key issues.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.whitehouse.gov/the-press-office/2013/03/08/statement-press-secretary-robert-levinson|title=Statement by the Press Secretary on Robert Levinson|work=The White House}}</ref></blockquote>\n\nSecretary of State [[John Kerry]] also met with Levinson's wife and son \"to reiterate that the U.S. government remains committed to locating Mr. Levinson and reuniting him safely with his family\".<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.reuters.com/article/2013/03/08/us-iran-kerry-levinson-idUSBRE9271B020130308|title=John Kerry meets with family of ex-FBI agent missing in Iran|work=Reuters}}</ref>\n\n== Reward ==\n[[File:Robert Levinson Reward.pdf|thumb|right|$20 million reward poster to help find Robert Levinson.]]\nOn March 6, 2012, approaching the fifth anniversary of Robert Levinson's captivity, the [[Federal Bureau of Investigation]] offered a $1-million reward for information leading to his safe recovery and return. In addition, a campaign was launched, using billboards, radio messages, flyers, and a telephone hotline to publicize this reward and obtain information of his whereabouts.<ref name=\"$1 Million Reward Offered for Missing Retired FBI Agent\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.fbi.gov/news/stories/2012/march/levinson/levinson |title=FBI \u2014 $1 Million Reward Offered for Missing Retired Agent |publisher=Fbi.gov |date= |access-date=2012-03-07}}</ref> In conjunction with this announced reward, the [[Society of Former Special Agents of the Federal Bureau of Investigation]] announced that it was giving the two youngest Levinson children $5,000 each to help with their college costs.<ref name=\"$1 Million Reward Offered for Missing Retired FBI Agent\" />\n\nOn March 9, 2015, the FBI increased the reward to up to $5 million for information regarding Levinson's whereabouts.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.fbi.gov/washingtondc/press-releases/2015/eight-year-anniversary-of-the-disappearance-of-robert-a.-levinson?utm_campaign|title=FBI \u2014 Eight Year Anniversary of the Disappearance of Robert A. Levinson|work=FBI}}</ref>\n\nOn November 4, 2019, the [[United States Department of State]] [[Rewards for Justice Program]] offered a $20 million reward for information leading to Levinson's whereabouts.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.fbi.gov/contact-us/field-offices/washingtondc/news/press-releases/fbi-washington-field-office-statement-on-robert-a-levinson-and-the-department-of-state-rewards-for-justice-announcement|title=FBI Washington Field Office Statement on Robert A. Levinson and the Department of State Rewards for Justice Announcement \u2014 FBI|website=www.fbi.gov}}</ref>\n\n== Proof of life ==\nAccording to the [[Associated Press]], Levinson's family received \"irrefutable proof\" of life late in 2010.<ref>{{cite web|author=ADAM GOLDMAN and MATT APUZZO Associated Press |url=http://abcnews.go.com/US/wireStory?id=13049751 |title=Years After Vanishing in Iran, US Man Proven Alive - ABC News |publisher=Abcnews.go.com |date=2011-03-03 |accessdate=2011-12-09}}</ref>  On December 9, 2011, the family released a hostage video they received in November 2010. In the video, Robert appears to have lost considerable weight, and repeatedly pleads for help in returning home.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.politico.com/news/stories/1211/70183.html |title=Robert Levinson, missing ex-FBI agent in hostage video: 'Help me' |work=[[Associated Press]]|date= December 9, 2011}}</ref>\n\nOn January 8, 2013, Levinson's family released photos to the media showing the former agent in an orange jumpsuit with overgrown and unkempt hair. A family spokesman told CNN the photographs were received in April 2011.  CNN reported: \"Asked why the family is releasing the images now, more than 18 months later, the spokesman said: 'The family is anxious that not enough is being done. There is frustration with the lack of progress on the case.'\"<ref name=Alive>{{cite news|url=http://www.cnn.com/2013/01/08/us/iran-missing-fbi-agent/index.html |title=Family releases photos of captive American |publisher=CNN.com |date=2013-01-10 |accessdate=2013-12-12}}</ref>\n\n== President Rouhani's statements ==\nIn an interview with CNN's [[Christiane Amanpour]] during his trip to the United Nations General Assembly in September 2013, Iranian President [[Hassan Rouhani]] spoke of cooperation regarding Levinson's case. \"We are willing to help, and all the intelligence services in the region can come together to gather information about him to find his whereabouts\", Rouhani told Amanpour, \"and we're willing to cooperate on that\".<ref name=\"cnn12dec\" />\n\nIn a subsequent interview with [[Charlie Rose]], Rouhani said, \"As to where his whereabouts when he disappeared, I personally have no information on those details, but naturally when someone disappears their family is suffering in specific.  Everyone must help.  It's natural that everyone must help\".<ref>{{Cite AV media |url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=pJaasDOpHsI |title=Charlie Rose asks Rouhani about Robert Levinson |publisher=YouTube |date=Sep 27, 2013 |author=mwolda |accessdate=2013-12-12 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130927154554/http://www.youtube.com/watch?v=pJaasDOpHsI |archivedate=2013-09-27 }}</ref>\n\n== President Obama's discussion of case with Rouhani ==\nDuring the Obama\u2013Rouhani phone call on September 27, 2013, the first communication between the presidents of the two countries in 34 years, President Obama noted his concern about Levinson's disappearance to Rouhani, and expressed his interest in seeing him reunited with his family.<ref name=\"cnn12dec\" />\n\n== United States Senate resolution ==\nOn May 11, 2015, the [[United States Senate]] voted on [[concurrent resolution]] 16 for the release of Robert Levinson, which passed in a unanimous decision without amendment.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/politics/congress/senate-passes-resolution-for-release-of-americans-in-iran/2015/05/11/fad52814-f82d-11e4-a47c-e56f4db884ed_story.html|title=Senate Passes Resolution for Release of Americans in Iran|author= Deb Riechmann|date=11 May 2015|publisher=|via=washingtonpost.com|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150528230412/http://www.washingtonpost.com/politics/congress/senate-passes-resolution-for-release-of-americans-in-iran/2015/05/11/fad52814-f82d-11e4-a47c-e56f4db884ed_story.html|archivedate=May 28, 2015}}</ref> This resolution states that it is U.S. policy that: (1) the government of the Islamic Republic of Iran should immediately release [[Saeed Abedini]], [[Amir Hekmati]], and [[Jason Rezaian]], and cooperate with the U.S. government to locate and return Robert Levinson; and (2) the U.S. government should undertake every effort using every diplomatic tool at its disposal to secure their release.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.congress.gov/bill/114th-congress/senate-concurrent-resolution/16|title=S.Con.Res.16 - 114th Congress (2015-2016): A concurrent resolution stating the policy of the United States regarding the release of United States citizens in Iran.|first=Risch|last=James|date=20 May 2015|website=www.congress.gov}}</ref>\n\n== Reported death ==\nIn March 2020, it was reported that Levinson's family and the United States government had concluded that it was likely that Levinson had died in Iranian custody before 2020.<ref name=\"dead\">{{Cite news |last=Goldman |first=Adam |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2020/03/25/us/politics/robert-levinson-cia-iran.html |title=Ex-F.B.I. Agent Who Vanished on C.I.A. Mission to Iran Is Likely Dead, U.S. Concludes |date=March 25, 2020 |work=The New York Times |access-date=March 25, 2020 |url-status=live |language=en-US |issn=0362-4331}}</ref>\n\n== See also ==\n{{portal|Biography|Iran|United States}}\n*[[List of people who disappeared mysteriously]]\n*[[List of foreign nationals detained in Iran]]\n{{clear}}\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*[https://www.facebook.com/helpboblevinson/ Help Bob Levinson] on [[Facebook]]\n*[http://helpboblevinson.spaces.live.com/ Help Bob Levinson]\n*[https://www.fbi.gov/wanted/kidnap/robert-a-levinson Bob Levinson wanted poster] [[FBI|FBI web site]], retrieved November 2019.\n\n{{Authority control}}\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Levinson, Robert}}\n\n[[Category:Drug Enforcement Administration agents]]\n[[Category:Federal Bureau of Investigation agents]]\n[[Category:American people taken hostage]]\n[[Category:Missing people]]\n[[Category:People of the Central Intelligence Agency]]\n[[Category:Iran\u2013United States relations]]\n[[Category:1948 births]]\n[[Category:Kidnappings in Iran]]\n[[Category:2000s missing person cases]]\n[[Category:CIA operatives in Iran]]\n[[Category:Date of death unknown]]\n[[Category:People from Flushing, Queens]]\n[[Category:People declared dead in absentia]]\n", "name_user": "2a01:e35:2ef3:a160:64aa:3bdc:73b5:d0fe", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Disappearance_of_Robert_Levinson"}
{"title_page": "LibreOffice Calc", "text_new": "{{short description|Spreadsheet component of LibreOffice}}\n{{primary sources|date=June 2013}}\n\n{{Infobox software\n| name                   = LibreOffice Calc\n| logo                   = LibreOffice 6.1 Calc Icon.svg\n| logo size              = 52px\n| screenshot             = [[File:LibreOffice Calc 6.2 screenshot.png|Libreoffice Calc 6.2|305px]]\n| caption                = Screenshot of LibreOffice Calc 6.2\n| collapsible            =\n| developer              = [[The Document Foundation]]\n| status                 = Active\n| latest release version = {{Latest stable software release/LibreOffice}}\n| latest release date    =\n| operating system       = [[Linux]], [[OS X]], [[Microsoft Windows]]<ref name=\"SystemReq\">{{Cite web|url = https://www.libreoffice.org/get-help/system-requirements/|title = System Requirements|accessdate = 8 September 2011|last = [[The Document Foundation]]|year = n.d.}}</ref> and [[FreeBSD]]<ref name=\"FreeBSD\">[http://www.freebsd.org/doc/en_US.ISO8859-1/books/handbook/desktop-productivity.html FreeBSD Handbook, 7.3.5 LibreOffice]</ref> \n| genre                  = [[Spreadsheet]]\n| license                = [[Mozilla Public License|MPLv2.0]] (secondary license [[GNU General Public License|GPL]], [[GNU Lesser General Public License|LGPLv3+]] or [[Apache License 2.0]])<ref name=\"About\">{{cite web\n    | title       = Licenses\n    | url         = https://www.libreoffice.org/download/license/\n    | publisher   = [[The Document Foundation]]\n    | accessdate  = 16 December 2015}}</ref>\n| website                = {{URL|https://www.libreoffice.org/discover/calc/}}\n}}\n'''LibreOffice Calc''' is the [[spreadsheet]] component of the [[LibreOffice]] software package.<ref name=\"CalcHome\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.libreoffice.org/discover/calc/|title=Calc, the LibreOffice spreadsheet program|publisher=[[The Document Foundation]]|accessdate=8 September 2011}}</ref><ref>{{cite book | first1=Richard | last1=Petersen | year=2011 | page=170 | title=Ubuntu 11. 04 Desktop Handbook | publisher=Surfing Turtle Press | isbn=1-936280-28-0 | url=https://books.google.com/books?id=CS7txn0x8OEC&pg=PA170 }}</ref>\n\nAfter forking from [[OpenOffice.org]] in 2010, LibreOffice Calc underwent a massive re-work of external reference handling to fix many defects in formula calculations involving external references, and to boost [[Cache (computing)|data caching]] performance, especially when referencing large data ranges.<ref name=\"34FF\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.libreoffice.org/download/3-4-new-features-and-fixes/|title=3.4 New Features and Fixes|publisher=[[The Document Foundation]]|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131214213702/https://www.libreoffice.org/download/3-4-new-features-and-fixes/|archive-date=14 December 2013|url-status=|accessdate=8 September 2011}}</ref>\n\nAdditionally, Calc now supports 1 million rows in a spreadsheet<ref name=\"PaulFeb11\">{{Cite web|url=https://arstechnica.com/information-technology/2011/01/the-document-foundation-announces-first-release-of-libreoffice/|title=First release of LibreOffice arrives with improvements over OOo|last=Paul|first=Ryan|date=25 January 2011|work=[[Ars Technica]]|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181127022527/https://arstechnica.com/information-technology/2011/01/the-document-foundation-announces-first-release-of-libreoffice/|archive-date=27 November 2018|url-status=live|accessdate=8 September 2011}}</ref> with macro references to each [[Cell (spreadsheet)|cell]].\n\nCalc is capable of opening and saving most spreadsheets in [[Microsoft Excel file format]].<ref name=\"CalcHome\" /> Calc is also capable of saving spreadsheets as [[PDF]] files.<ref name=\"CalcHome\" />\n\nAs with the entire LibreOffice suite, Calc is available for a variety of platforms, including [[Linux]], [[macOS]], [[Microsoft Windows]],<ref name=\"SystemReq\"/> and [[FreeBSD]].<ref name=\"FreeBSD\"/> Available under the [[Mozilla Public License]], Calc is [[free and open-source software]].<ref name=\"Lic\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.libreoffice.org/download/license/|title=Licenses|publisher=[[The Document Foundation]]|accessdate=21 June 2011}}</ref>\n\nThere is now a closed beta of LibreOffice on [[AmigaOS]] 4.1.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.generationamiga.com/2017/02/28/new-beta-libreoffice-for-amigaos-4-1/|title=New beta LibreOffice for AmigaOS 4.1|date=28 February 2017|website=GenerationAmiga.com}}</ref>\n\n==Features==\nCapabilities of Calc include:\n* Ability to read/write [[OpenDocument]] (ODF), Excel (XLS), [[Comma-separated values|CSV]],<ref name=\"CSV\">{{Cite web|url=https://help.libreoffice.org/Calc/Importing_and_Exporting_CSV_Files|title=Importing and Exporting CSV Files|website=LibreOffice Help|publisher=[[The Document Foundation]]|accessdate=8 September 2011}}</ref> and several other formats.<ref name=\"OtherFormats\">{{Cite web|url=https://help.libreoffice.org/Common/About_Import_and_Export_Filters|title=About Import and Export Filters|website=LibreOffice Help|publisher=[[The Document Foundation]]|accessdate=8 September 2011}}</ref><ref name=\"OOXML\">{{Cite web|url=https://wiki.documentfoundation.org/LibreOffice_OOXML|title=The Document Foundation, LibreOffice and OOXML|website=The Document Foundation Wiki|publisher=[[The Document Foundation]]|accessdate=8 September 2011}}</ref>\n* Support for many functions, including those for [[imaginary number]]s, as well as financial and statistical functions.<ref name=\"Financial\">{{Cite web|url=https://help.libreoffice.org/Calc/Financial_Functions_Part_One|title=Financial Functions Part One|website=LibreOffice Help|publisher=[[The Document Foundation]]|accessdate=8 September 2011}}</ref><ref name=\"Imaginary\">{{Cite web|url=https://help.libreoffice.org/Calc/Add-in_Functions,_List_of_Analysis_Functions_Part_Two#IMAGINARY|title=Add-in Functions, List of Analysis Functions Part Two|website=LibreOffice Help|publisher=[[The Document Foundation]]|accessdate=8 September 2011}}</ref>\n* Supports 1 million rows in a spreadsheet, making LibreOffice spreadsheets more suitable for heavier scientific or financial spreadsheets.<ref name=\"LOFF331\" /> However, the number of columns is restricted to at most 1024, much lower than Excel's limit of 16384.<ref>[https://bugs.freedesktop.org/show_bug.cgi?id=50916 Bug 50916 - Allow more than 1024 columns in calc]</ref>\n*Up to now, new functions such as IFS, Switch TEXT JOIN, MAXIFS, MINIFS functions, etc. were available only in Excel 2016 and later. Libre Office Calc can use them.\n\nIn its internal data structure, Calc until version 4.1 relies on cells as the [[base class]] throughout, which has been blamed for \"extreme memory use, slow computation, and difficult code\". Version 4.2 (released in January 2014) addresses these issues by instead storing the data in [[Array data structure|arrays]] where possible.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://lwn.net/Articles/571291/|title=A LibreOffice Update|last=Corbet|first=Jonathan|date=23 October 2013|website=[[LWN.net]]}}</ref>\n\n===Pivot Table===\nOriginally called DataPilot,<ref name=\"34FF\" /> Pivot Table provides similar functionality to the [[Pivot table]] found in [[Microsoft Excel]]. It is used for interactive table layout and dynamic data analysis.<ref name=\"PivotTable\">{{Cite web|url=https://help.libreoffice.org/Calc/Pivot_Table|title=Pivot Table|website=LibreOffice Help|publisher=[[The Document Foundation]]|accessdate=13 November 2011}}</ref>\n\nPivot table has support for an unlimited number of fields. Previously Pivot Table only supported up to 8 column/row/data fields and up to 10 page fields.<ref name=\"34FF\" />\n\nAn advanced sort macro is included that allows data to be arranged or categorised based on either a user generated macro or one of several default included macros.<ref name=\"LOFF331\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.libreoffice.org/download/3-3-new-features-and-fixes/|title=3.3 New Features and Fixes|year=2011|website=LibreOffice|publisher=[[The Document Foundation]]|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140227184750/https://www.libreoffice.org/download/3-3-new-features-and-fixes/|archive-date=27 February 2014|url-status=|accessdate=29 July 2011}}</ref>\n\n==Release history==\nCalc has continued to diverge since the fork from its parent OpenOffice with new features being added and code cleanups taking place.<ref name=\"Noyes03Jun11\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.pcworld.com/article/229353/despite_oracles_antics_libreoffice_gets_a_big_update.html|title=Despite Oracle's Antics, LibreOffice Gets a Big Update|last=Noyes|first=Katherine|date=3 June 2011|work=[[PC World (magazine)|PC World]]|accessdate=8 September 2011}}</ref>\n[[File:Libreoffice Calc in Linux.png|thumb|Screenshot of Libre Office Calc in Linux ([[Ubuntu]])]]\n'''Versions for LibreOffice Calc include the following:'''\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! Year Released\n! Version\n! Comments\n|-\n| 2011-06-16\n| 3.3.3\n|\n* More-familiar default key bindings.<ref name=\"McAllister16Feb11\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.infoworld.com/print/151716/|title=Open office dilemma: OpenOffice.org vs. LibreOffice|last=McAllister|first=Neil|date=16 February 2011|work=[[InfoWorld]]|accessdate=8 September 2011|archive-url=https://archive.today/20131001035953/http://www.infoworld.com/print/151716|archive-date=1 October 2013|url-status=live}}</ref>\n* Toolbar icon for toggling sheet grids in Calc similar to Excel.<ref name=\"LOFF331\" />\n* Improved Excel interoperability.<ref name=\"LOFF331\" />\n* Documents drawn with the UNO api can be inserted in calc.<ref name=\"LOFF331\" />\n* New options for CSV (Comma-Separated Value) importation in Calc, allowing the import of custom delimited files common in engineering scenarios.\n* Support for 3 different formula syntaxes: Calc A1, Excel A1 and Excel R1C1.<ref name=\"LOFF331\" />\n* 1 million rows in a spreadsheet in Calc, making Calc more suitable for heavier scientific or financial spreadsheets.<ref name=\"LOFF331\" />\n|-\n| 2011-06-03\n| 3.4.0\n|\n* Re-work of the drawing layer, to improve precision on re-positioning and re-sizing of drawing objects.<ref name=\"34FF\" />\n* Support for unlimited number of fields: Previously DataPilot only supported up to 8 column/row/data fields and up to 10 page fields. 3.4 has lifted this restriction to allow unlimited number of fields in each field type.<ref name=\"34FF\" />\n* Previously, Calc only supported named ranges in global scope, that is, all named ranges were made available for the entire document regardless of the current sheet. In 3.4 Calc now supports named ranges that are local to a sheet. The named range dialog (Insert->Names->Define) has been modified to reflect this change.<ref name=\"34FF\" />\n* Now preserves OLE links to other Excel documents when importing an Excel document. OLE links get converted to external references upon import. *Previously, Calc ignored OLE links and cells containing OLE links resulted in error upon import.<ref name=\"34FF\" />\n* Multiple subtotals on a single sheet: It is now possible to define more than one subtotal range in a single sheet via Data->Subtotals. Previously, setting a second subtotal range removed the first one if they were on the same sheet.<ref name=\"34FF\" />\n|-\n| 2012-02-15\n| 3.5.0<ref name=\"DF14Feb12\">{{cite web|url=https://blog.documentfoundation.org/blog/2012/02/14/the-document-foundation-announces-libreoffice-3-5-the-best-free-office-suite-ever/|title=The Document Foundation announces LibreOffice 3.5: \"the best free office suite ever\"|last=Vignoli|first=Italo|date=14 February 2012|publisher=[[The Document Foundation]]}}</ref>\n|\n* support for up to 10,000 sheets<ref name=\"DF14Feb12\" />\n* a new multi-line input area<ref name=\"DF14Feb12\" />\n* new Calc functions conforming to the ODF OpenFormula specifications<ref name=\"DF14Feb12\" />\n* better performance when importing files from other office suites<ref name=\"DF14Feb12\" />\n* multiple selections in autofilter<ref name=\"DF14Feb12\" />\n* unlimited number of rules for conditional formatting<ref name=\"DF14Feb12\" /><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.libreoffice.org/download/3-5-new-features-and-fixes/|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131124100155/https://www.libreoffice.org/download/3-5-new-features-and-fixes/|url-status=dead|archive-date=2013-11-24|title=3.5 New Features and Fixes|publisher=[[The Document Foundation]]}}</ref>\n|-\n| 2012-08-08\n| 3.6.0\n|\n* Improved OOXML and ODF1.2 support<ref name=\"ReleaseNotes36\">{{Cite web|url=https://wiki.documentfoundation.org/ReleaseNotes/3.6|title=LibreOffice 3.6: Release Notes|website=The Document Foundation Wiki|publisher=[[The Document Foundation]]|accessdate=3 November 2013}}</ref>\n* Improved CSV file import<ref name=\"ReleaseNotes36\" />\n* Added a \"Save cell formulas instead of calculated values\" option to CSV export<ref name=\"ReleaseNotes36\" />\n* New spreadsheet functions<ref name=\"ReleaseNotes36\" />\n* GUI improvements<ref name=\"ReleaseNotes36\" />\n* Remove the limitation to 3 sort entries in calc<ref name=\"ReleaseNotes36\" />\n* Improved performance<ref name=\"ReleaseNotes36\" />\n|-\n| 2013-02-07\n| 4.0.0\n|\n* Improved performance<ref name=\"ReleaseNotes40\">{{Cite web|url=https://wiki.documentfoundation.org/ReleaseNotes/4.0|title=LibreOffice 4.0: Release Notes|website=The Document Foundation Wiki|publisher=[[The Document Foundation]]|accessdate=3 November 2013}}</ref>\n* Increased size limit on (uncompressed) ODF documents<ref name=\"ReleaseNotes40\" />\n* Easier XML import<ref name=\"ReleaseNotes40\" />\n* Improved conditional formats<ref name=\"ReleaseNotes40\" />\n* initial support for the file format of [[gnumeric]]<ref name=\"ReleaseNotes40\" />\n* New spreadsheet functions<ref name=\"ReleaseNotes40\" />\n|-\n| 2013-07-25\n| 4.1.0\n|\n* Embedding fonts in a Calc spreadsheet<ref name=\"ReleaseNotes41\">{{Cite web|url=https://wiki.documentfoundation.org/ReleaseNotes/4.1|title=LibreOffice 4.1: Release Notes|website=The Document Foundation Wiki|publisher=[[The Document Foundation]]|accessdate=3 November 2013}}</ref>\n* Add a Stepped Lines line type to Line and XY (Scatter) graphs<ref name=\"ReleaseNotes41\" />\n* Count the number of selected cells<ref name=\"ReleaseNotes41\" />\n* Import large HTML documents with more than 64k table cells<ref name=\"ReleaseNotes41\" />\n* New spreadsheet functions<ref name=\"ReleaseNotes41\" />\n* Improved hyphenation<ref name=\"ReleaseNotes41\" />\n\n|-\n| 2014-01-30\n| 4.2.0\n|\n* New spreadsheet functions<ref name=\"ReleaseNotes42\">{{Cite web|url=https://wiki.documentfoundation.org/ReleaseNotes/4.2|title=LibreOffice 4.2: Release Notes|website=The Document Foundation Wiki|publisher=[[The Document Foundation]]|accessdate=3 January 2014}}</ref>\n*[[Random number generation]] (non-dynamic)<ref name=\"ReleaseNotes42\" />\n* Statistics toolkit<ref name=\"ReleaseNotes42\" />\n* Other features: Redesign of data structures and Calc core to use OpenCL, threading and dynamic data storage\n|-\n| 2014-07-30\n| 4.3.0\n|\n* Smarter highlighting of cell in formula<ref name=\"ReleaseNotes43\">{{Cite web|url=https://wiki.documentfoundation.org/ReleaseNotes/4.3#Calc|title=LibreOffice 4.3: Release Notes {{!}} Calc|website=The Document Foundation Wiki|publisher=[[The Document Foundation]]|accessdate=14 April 2015}}</ref>\n* Number of selected rows and columns shown in the status bar<ref name=\"ReleaseNotes43\" />\n* Allow starting of cell edit with the content of the cell above it as its initial content.<ref name=\"ReleaseNotes43\" />\n* User selectable text conversion models.<ref name=\"ReleaseNotes43\" />\n* Pivot Table layout improvement.<ref name=\"ReleaseNotes43\" />\n* Add 34 new spreadsheet functions.<ref name=\"ReleaseNotes43\" />\n* Enable [https://projects.coin-or.org/CoinMP CoinMP] solver for additional options to previously enabled [[Linear programming#Solvers and scripting (programming) languages|LpSolve]].<ref name=\"ReleaseNotes43\" />\n* Added three Statistics Wizard options.<ref name=\"ReleaseNotes43\" />\n* Additional functionality to random number generator.<ref name=\"ReleaseNotes43\" />\n|-\n| 2015-01-29\n| 4.4.0\n|\n* Added three Statistics Wizard options.<ref name=\"ReleaseNotes44\">{{Cite web|url=https://wiki.documentfoundation.org/ReleaseNotes/4.4#Calc|title=LibreOffice 4.4: Release Notes {{!}} Calc|website=The Document Foundation Wiki|publisher=[[The Document Foundation]]|accessdate=14 April 2015}}</ref>\n* Add direct conversion of formulas to static values.<ref name=\"ReleaseNotes44\" />\n* Add one new spreadsheet function.<ref name=\"ReleaseNotes44\" />\n* Toolbar improvements<ref name=\"ReleaseNotes44\" />\n* Add sheet context menu.<ref name=\"ReleaseNotes44\" />\n|-\n| 2015-08-05\n| 5.0.0\n|\n* Added optional ability to repeat pivot table item labels.<ref name=\"ReleaseNotes50\">{{Cite web|url=https://wiki.documentfoundation.org/ReleaseNotes/5.0#Calc|title=LibreOffice 5.0: Release Notes {{!}} Calc|website=The Document Foundation Wiki|publisher=[[The Document Foundation]]|accessdate=6 August 2015}}</ref>\n* Added additional conditional formatting options.<ref name=\"ReleaseNotes50\" />\n* Improvements to XLSX import and export.<ref name=\"ReleaseNotes50\" />\n* Additional engineering notation options<ref name=\"ReleaseNotes50\" />\n* Improvements to table structured references.<ref name=\"ReleaseNotes50\" />\n* New spreadsheet functions and improvements to function import and export.<ref name=\"ReleaseNotes50\" />\n* Added capabilities in references of entire column/row (A:A / 1:1).<ref name=\"ReleaseNotes50\" />\n* Added ability to crop, change, and save an image.<ref name=\"ReleaseNotes50\" />\n* Toolbar improvements.<ref name=\"ReleaseNotes50\" />\n|}\n\n==See also==\n{{Portal|Free and open-source software}}\n* [[List of spreadsheet software]]\n* [[Comparison of spreadsheet software]]\n{{-}}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n{{commons category|Screenshots of LibreOffice Calc}}\n* {{Official website|https://www.libreoffice.org/discover/calc/}}\n\n{{Spreadsheets}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Libreoffice.Org Calc}}\n[[Category:Cross-platform free software]]\n[[Category:Free spreadsheet software]]\n[[Category:LibreOffice|Calc]]\n[[Category:Spreadsheet software]]\n[[Category:Spreadsheet software for macOS]]\n[[Category:Spreadsheet software for Windows]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Spreadsheet component of LibreOffice}}\n{{primary sources|date=June 2013}}\n\n{{Infobox software\n| name                   = LibreOffice Calc\n| logo                   = LibreOffice 6.1 Calc Icon.svg\n| logo size              = 52px\n| screenshot             = [[File:LibreOffice Calc 6.2 screenshot.png|Libreoffice Calc 6.2|305px]]\n| caption                = Screenshot of LibreOffice Calc 6.2\n| collapsible            =\n| developer              = [[The Document Foundation]]\n| status                 = Active\n| latest release version = {{Latest stable software release/LibreOffice}}\n| latest release date    =\n| operating system       = [[Linux]], [[OS X]], [[Microsoft Windows]]<ref name=\"SystemReq\">{{Cite web|url = https://www.libreoffice.org/get-help/system-requirements/|title = System Requirements|accessdate = 8 September 2011|last = [[The Document Foundation]]|year = n.d.}}</ref> and [[FreeBSD]]<ref name=\"FreeBSD\">[http://www.freebsd.org/doc/en_US.ISO8859-1/books/handbook/desktop-productivity.html FreeBSD Handbook, 7.3.5 LibreOffice]</ref> \n| genre                  = [[Spreadsheet]]\n| license                = [[Mozilla Public License|MPLv2.0]] (secondary license [[GNU General Public License|GPL]], [[GNU Lesser General Public License|LGPLv3+]] or [[Apache License 2.0]])<ref name=\"About\">{{cite web\n    | title       = Licenses\n    | url         = https://www.libreoffice.org/download/license/\n    | publisher   = [[The Document Foundation]]\n    | accessdate  = 16 December 2015}}</ref>\n| website                = {{URL|https://www.libreoffice.org/discover/calc/}}\n}}\n'''LibreOffice Calc''' is the [[spreadsheet]] component of the [[LibreOffice]] software package.<ref name=\"CalcHome\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.libreoffice.org/discover/calc/|title=Calc, the LibreOffice spreadsheet program|publisher=[[The Document Foundation]]|accessdate=8 September 2011}}</ref><ref>{{cite book | first1=Richard | last1=Petersen | year=2011 | page=170 | title=Ubuntu 11. 04 Desktop Handbook | publisher=Surfing Turtle Press | isbn=1-936280-28-0 | url=https://books.google.com/books?id=CS7txn0x8OEC&pg=PA170 }}</ref>\n\nAfter forking from [[OpenOffice.org]] in 2010, LibreOffice Calc underwent a massive re-work of external reference handling to fix many defects in formula calculations involving external references, and to boost [[Cache (computing)|data caching]] performance, especially when referencing large data ranges.<ref name=\"34FF\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.libreoffice.org/download/3-4-new-features-and-fixes/|title=3.4 New Features and Fixes|publisher=[[The Document Foundation]]|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131214213702/https://www.libreoffice.org/download/3-4-new-features-and-fixes/|archive-date=14 December 2013|url-status=|accessdate=8 September 2011}}</ref>\n\nAdditionally, Calc now supports 1 million rows in a spreadsheet<ref name=\"PaulFeb11\">{{Cite web|url=https://arstechnica.com/information-technology/2011/01/the-document-foundation-announces-first-release-of-libreoffice/|title=First release of LibreOffice arrives with improvements over OOo|last=Paul|first=Ryan|date=25 January 2011|work=[[Ars Technica]]|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181127022527/https://arstechnica.com/information-technology/2011/01/the-document-foundation-announces-first-release-of-libreoffice/|archive-date=27 November 2018|url-status=live|accessdate=8 September 2011}}</ref> with macro references to each [[Cell (spreadsheet)|cell]].\n\nCalc is capable of opening and saving most spreadsheets in [[Microsoft Excel file format]].<ref name=\"CalcHome\" /> Calc is also capable of saving spreadsheets as [[PDF]] files.<ref name=\"CalcHome\" />\n\nAs with the entire LibreOffice suite, Calc is available for a variety of platforms, including [[Linux]], [[macOS]], [[Microsoft Windows]],<ref name=\"SystemReq\"/> and [[FreeBSD]].<ref name=\"FreeBSD\"/> Available under the [[Mozilla Public License]], Calc is [[free and open-source software]].<ref name=\"Lic\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.libreoffice.org/download/license/|title=Licenses|publisher=[[The Document Foundation]]|accessdate=21 June 2011}}</ref>\n\nThere is now a closed beta of LibreOffice on [[AmigaOS]] 4.1.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.generationamiga.com/2017/02/28/new-beta-libreoffice-for-amigaos-4-1/|title=New beta LibreOffice for AmigaOS 4.1|date=28 February 2017|website=GenerationAmiga.com}}</ref>\n\n==Features==\nCapabilities of Calc include:\n* Ability to read/write [[OpenDocument]] (ODF), Excel (XLS), [[Comma-separated values|CSV]],<ref name=\"CSV\">{{Cite web|url=https://help.libreoffice.org/Calc/Importing_and_Exporting_CSV_Files|title=Importing and Exporting CSV Files|website=LibreOffice Help|publisher=[[The Document Foundation]]|accessdate=8 September 2011}}</ref> and several other formats.<ref name=\"OtherFormats\">{{Cite web|url=https://help.libreoffice.org/Common/About_Import_and_Export_Filters|title=About Import and Export Filters|website=LibreOffice Help|publisher=[[The Document Foundation]]|accessdate=8 September 2011}}</ref><ref name=\"OOXML\">{{Cite web|url=https://wiki.documentfoundation.org/LibreOffice_OOXML|title=The Document Foundation, LibreOffice and OOXML|website=The Document Foundation Wiki|publisher=[[The Document Foundation]]|accessdate=8 September 2011}}</ref>\n* Support for many functions, including those for [[imaginary number]]s, as well as financial and statistical functions.<ref name=\"Financial\">{{Cite web|url=https://help.libreoffice.org/Calc/Financial_Functions_Part_One|title=Financial Functions Part One|website=LibreOffice Help|publisher=[[The Document Foundation]]|accessdate=8 September 2011}}</ref><ref name=\"Imaginary\">{{Cite web|url=https://help.libreoffice.org/Calc/Add-in_Functions,_List_of_Analysis_Functions_Part_Two#IMAGINARY|title=Add-in Functions, List of Analysis Functions Part Two|website=LibreOffice Help|publisher=[[The Document Foundation]]|accessdate=8 September 2011}}</ref>\n* Supports 1 million rows in a spreadsheet, making LibreOffice spreadsheets more suitable for heavier scientific or financial spreadsheets.<ref name=\"LOFF331\" /> However, the number of columns is restricted to at most 1024, much lower than Excel's limit of 16384.<ref>[https://bugs.freedesktop.org/show_bug.cgi?id=50916 Bug 50916 - Allow more than 1024 columns in calc]</ref>\n*Up to now, new functions such as IFS, Switch TEXT JOIN, MAXIFS, MINIFS functions, etc. were available only in Excel 2016 and later. Libre Office Calc can use them.\n\nIn its internal data structure, Calc until version 4.1 relies on cells as the [[base class]] throughout, which has been blamed for \"extreme memory use, slow computation, and difficult code\". Version 4.2 (released in January 2014) addresses these issues by instead storing the data in [[Array data structure|arrays]] where possible.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://lwn.net/Articles/571291/|title=A LibreOffice Update|last=Corbet|first=Jonathan|date=23 October 2013|website=[[LWN.net]]}}</ref>\n\n===Pivot Table===\nOriginally called DataPilot,<ref name=\"34FF\" /> Pivot Table provides similar functionality to the [[Pivot table]] found in [[Microsoft Excel]]. It is used for interactive table layout and dynamic data analysis.<ref name=\"PivotTable\">{{Cite web|url=https://help.libreoffice.org/Calc/Pivot_Table|title=Pivot Table|website=LibreOffice Help|publisher=[[The Document Foundation]]|accessdate=13 November 2011}}</ref>\n\nPivot table has support for an unlimited number of fields. Previously Pivot Table only supported up to 8 column/row/data fields and up to 10 page fields.<ref name=\"34FF\" />\n\nAn advanced sort macro is included that allows data to be arranged or categorised based on either a user generated macro or one of several default included macros.<ref name=\"LOFF331\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.libreoffice.org/download/3-3-new-features-and-fixes/|title=3.3 New Features and Fixes|year=2011|website=LibreOffice|publisher=[[The Document Foundation]]|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140227184750/https://www.libreoffice.org/download/3-3-new-features-and-fixes/|archive-date=27 February 2014|url-status=|accessdate=29 July 2011}}</ref>\n\n==Release history==\nCalc has continued to diverge since the fork from its parent OpenOffice with new features being added and code cleanups taking place.<ref name=\"Noyes03Jun11\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.pcworld.com/article/229353/despite_oracles_antics_libreoffice_gets_a_big_update.html|title=Despite Oracle's Antics, LibreOffice Gets a Big Update|last=Noyes|first=Katherine|date=3 June 2011|work=[[PC World (magazine)|PC World]]|accessdate=8 September 2011}}</ref>\n[[File:Libreoffice Calc in Linux.png|thumb|Screenshot of Libre Office Calc in Linux ([[Ubuntu]])]]\n'''Versions for LibreOffice Calc include the following:'''\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! Year Released\n! Version\n! Comments\n|-\n| 2011-06-16\n| 3.3.3\n|\n* More-familiar default key bindings.<ref name=\"McAllister16Feb11\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.infoworld.com/print/151716/|title=Open office dilemma: OpenOffice.org vs. LibreOffice|last=McAllister|first=Neil|date=16 February 2011|work=[[InfoWorld]]|accessdate=8 September 2011|archive-url=https://archive.today/20131001035953/http://www.infoworld.com/print/151716|archive-date=1 October 2013|url-status=live}}</ref>\n* Toolbar icon for toggling sheet grids in Calc similar to Excel.<ref name=\"LOFF331\" />\n* Improved Excel interoperability.<ref name=\"LOFF331\" />\n* Documents drawn with the UNO api can be inserted in calc.<ref name=\"LOFF331\" />\n* New options for CSV (Comma-Separated Value) importation in Calc, allowing the import of custom delimited files common in engineering scenarios.\n* Support for 3 different formula syntaxes: Calc A1, Excel A1 and Excel R1C1.<ref name=\"LOFF331\" />\n* 1 million rows in a spreadsheet in Calc, making Calc more suitable for heavier scientific or financial spreadsheets.<ref name=\"LOFF331\" />\n|-\n| 2011-06-03\n| 3.4.0\n|\n* Re-work of the drawing layer, to improve precision on re-positioning and re-sizing of drawing objects.<ref name=\"34FF\" />\n* Support for unlimited number of fields: Previously DataPilot only supported up to 8 column/row/data fields and up to 10 page fields. 3.4 has lifted this restriction to allow unlimited number of fields in each field type.<ref name=\"34FF\" />\n* Previously, Calc only supported named ranges in global scope, that is, all named ranges were made available for the entire document regardless of the current sheet. In 3.4 Calc now supports named ranges that are local to a sheet. The named range dialog (Insert->Names->Define) has been modified to reflect this change.<ref name=\"34FF\" />\n* Now preserves OLE links to other Excel documents when importing an Excel document. OLE links get converted to external references upon import. *Previously, Calc ignored OLE links and cells containing OLE links resulted in error upon import.<ref name=\"34FF\" />\n* Multiple subtotals on a single sheet: It is now possible to define more than one subtotal range in a single sheet via Data->Subtotals. Previously, setting a second subtotal range removed the first one if they were on the same sheet.<ref name=\"34FF\" />\n|-\n| 2012-02-15\n| 3.5.0<ref name=\"DF14Feb12\">{{cite web|url=https://blog.documentfoundation.org/blog/2012/02/14/the-document-foundation-announces-libreoffice-3-5-the-best-free-office-suite-ever/|title=The Document Foundation announces LibreOffice 3.5: \"the best free office suite ever\"|last=Vignoli|first=Italo|date=14 February 2012|publisher=[[The Document Foundation]]}}</ref>\n|\n* support for up to 10,000 sheets<ref name=\"DF14Feb12\" />\n* a new multi-line input area<ref name=\"DF14Feb12\" />\n* new Calc functions conforming to the ODF OpenFormula specifications<ref name=\"DF14Feb12\" />\n* better performance when importing files from other office suites<ref name=\"DF14Feb12\" />\n* multiple selections in autofilter<ref name=\"DF14Feb12\" />\n* unlimited number of rules for conditional formatting<ref name=\"DF14Feb12\" /><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.libreoffice.org/download/3-5-new-features-and-fixes/|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131124100155/https://www.libreoffice.org/download/3-5-new-features-and-fixes/|url-status=dead|archive-date=2013-11-24|title=3.5 New Features and Fixes|publisher=[[The Document Foundation]]}}</ref>\n|-\n| 2012-08-08\n| 3.6.0\n|\n* Improved OOXML and ODF1.2 support<ref name=\"ReleaseNotes36\">{{Cite web|url=https://wiki.documentfoundation.org/ReleaseNotes/3.6|title=LibreOffice 3.6: Release Notes|website=The Document Foundation Wiki|publisher=[[The Document Foundation]]|accessdate=3 November 2013}}</ref>\n* Improved CSV file import<ref name=\"ReleaseNotes36\" />\n* Added a \"Save cell formulas instead of calculated values\" option to CSV export<ref name=\"ReleaseNotes36\" />\n* New spreadsheet functions<ref name=\"ReleaseNotes36\" />\n* GUI improvements<ref name=\"ReleaseNotes36\" />\n* Remove the limitation to 3 sort entries in calc<ref name=\"ReleaseNotes36\" />\n* Improved performance<ref name=\"ReleaseNotes36\" />\n|-\n| 2013-02-07\n| 4.0.0\n|\n* Improved performance<ref name=\"ReleaseNotes40\">{{Cite web|url=https://wiki.documentfoundation.org/ReleaseNotes/4.0|title=LibreOffice 4.0: Release Notes|website=The Document Foundation Wiki|publisher=[[The Document Foundation]]|accessdate=3 November 2013}}</ref>\n* Increased size limit on (uncompressed) ODF documents<ref name=\"ReleaseNotes40\" />\n* Easier XML import<ref name=\"ReleaseNotes40\" />\n* Improved conditional formats<ref name=\"ReleaseNotes40\" />\n* initial support for the file format of [[gnumeric]]<ref name=\"ReleaseNotes40\" />\n* New spreadsheet functions<ref name=\"ReleaseNotes40\" />\n|-\n| 2013-07-25\n| 4.1.0\n|\n* Embedding fonts in a Calc spreadsheet<ref name=\"ReleaseNotes41\">{{Cite web|url=https://wiki.documentfoundation.org/ReleaseNotes/4.1|title=LibreOffice 4.1: Release Notes|website=The Document Foundation Wiki|publisher=[[The Document Foundation]]|accessdate=3 November 2013}}</ref>\n* Add a Stepped Lines line type to Line and XY (Scatter) graphs<ref name=\"ReleaseNotes41\" />\n* Count the number of selected cells<ref name=\"ReleaseNotes41\" />\n* Import large HTML documents with more than 64k table cells<ref name=\"ReleaseNotes41\" />\n* New spreadsheet functions<ref name=\"ReleaseNotes41\" />\n* Improved hyphenation<ref name=\"ReleaseNotes41\" />\n\n|-\n| 2014-01-30\n| 4.2.0\n|\n* New spreadsheet functions<ref name=\"ReleaseNotes42\">{{Cite web|url=https://wiki.documentfoundation.org/ReleaseNotes/4.2|title=LibreOffice 4.2: Release Notes|website=The Document Foundation Wiki|publisher=[[The Document Foundation]]|accessdate=3 January 2014}}</ref>\n*[[Random number generation]] (non-dynamic)<ref name=\"ReleaseNotes42\" />\n* Statistics toolkit<ref name=\"ReleaseNotes42\" />\n* Other features: Redesign of data structures and Calc core to use OpenCL, threading and dynamic data storage\n|-\n| 2014-07-30\n| 4.3.0\n|\n* Smarter highlighting of cell in formula<ref name=\"ReleaseNotes43\">{{Cite web|url=https://wiki.documentfoundation.org/ReleaseNotes/4.3#Calc|title=LibreOffice 4.3: Release Notes {{!}} Calc|website=The Document Foundation Wiki|publisher=[[The Document Foundation]]|accessdate=14 April 2015}}</ref>\n* Number of selected rows and columns shown in the status bar<ref name=\"ReleaseNotes43\" />\n* Allow starting of cell edit with the content of the cell above it as its initial content.<ref name=\"ReleaseNotes43\" />\n* User selectable text conversion models.<ref name=\"ReleaseNotes43\" />\n* Pivot Table layout improvement.<ref name=\"ReleaseNotes43\" />\n* Add 34 new spreadsheet functions.<ref name=\"ReleaseNotes43\" />\n* Enable [https://projects.coin-or.org/CoinMP CoinMP] solver for additional options to previously enabled [[Linear programming#Solvers and scripting (programming) languages|LpSolve]].<ref name=\"ReleaseNotes43\" />\n* Added three Statistics Wizard options.<ref name=\"ReleaseNotes43\" />\n* Additional functionality to random number generator.<ref name=\"ReleaseNotes43\" />\n|-\n| 2015-01-29\n| 4.4.0\n|\n* Added three Statistics Wizard options.<ref name=\"ReleaseNotes44\">{{Cite web|url=https://wiki.documentfoundation.org/ReleaseNotes/4.4#Calc|title=LibreOffice 4.4: Release Notes {{!}} Calc|website=The Document Foundation Wiki|publisher=[[The Document Foundation]]|accessdate=14 April 2015}}</ref>\n* Add direct conversion of formulas to static values.<ref name=\"ReleaseNotes44\" />\n* Add one new spreadsheet function.<ref name=\"ReleaseNotes44\" />\n* Toolbar improvements<ref name=\"ReleaseNotes44\" />\n* Add sheet context menu.<ref name=\"ReleaseNotes44\" />\n|-\n| 2015-08-05\n| 5.0.0\n|\n* Added optional ability to repeat pivot table item labels.<ref name=\"ReleaseNotes50\">{{Cite web|url=https://wiki.documentfoundation.org/ReleaseNotes/5.0#Calc|title=LibreOffice 5.0: Release Notes {{!}} Calc|website=The Document Foundation Wiki|publisher=[[The Document Foundation]]|accessdate=6 August 2015}}</ref>\n* Added additional conditional formatting options.<ref name=\"ReleaseNotes50\" />\n* Improvements to XLSX import and export.<ref name=\"ReleaseNotes50\" />\n* Additional engineering notation options<ref name=\"ReleaseNotes50\" />\n* Improvements to table structured references.<ref name=\"ReleaseNotes50\" />\n* New spreadsheet functions and improvements to function import and export.<ref name=\"ReleaseNotes50\" />\n* Added capabilities in references of entire column/row (A:A / 1:1).<ref name=\"ReleaseNotes50\" />\n* Added ability to crop, change, and save an image.<ref name=\"ReleaseNotes50\" />\n* Toolbar improvements.<ref name=\"ReleaseNotes50\" />\n|}\n\n==See also==\n{{Portal|Free and open-source software}}\n* [[List of spreadsheet software]]\n* [[Comparison of spreadsheets]]\n{{-}}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n{{commons category|Screenshots of LibreOffice Calc}}\n* {{Official website|https://www.libreoffice.org/discover/calc/}}\n\n{{Spreadsheets}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Libreoffice.Org Calc}}\n[[Category:Cross-platform free software]]\n[[Category:Free spreadsheet software]]\n[[Category:LibreOffice|Calc]]\n[[Category:Spreadsheet software]]\n[[Category:Spreadsheet software for macOS]]\n[[Category:Spreadsheet software for Windows]]\n", "name_user": "Tea2min", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eSee also:Skip redirect.Comparison of spreadsheetsredirects toComparison of spreadsheet software.", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/LibreOffice_Calc"}
{"title_page": "Joe Brown (climber)", "text_new": "{{Use British English|date=August 2011}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=August 2011}}\n[[File:Joe Brown.jpg|thumb|right|200px|Brown in the 1990s]]\n'''Joseph Brown''', usually '''Joe Brown''', {{post-nominals|country=GBR|size=100%|commas=on|CBE}} (26 September 1930 - 15 April 2020) is an English [[Climbing|climber]]. He is regarded as the outstanding pioneering English rock climber of the 1950s and early 1960s.\n\nBrown established a number of new routes in [[Snowdonia]] and the [[Peak District]] that were at the leading edge of the hardest grades. He made ascents in the Alps in the 1950s with others and, in 1955, the first ascent of the world's third highest mountain, [[Kangchenjunga]] in the [[Nepal]]ese [[Himalaya]], with [[George Band]]. In 1956 he made the first ascent of the west summit of the [[Muztagh Tower]] in the [[Karakoram]] with [[Ian McNaught-Davis]].\n\nBrown helped create new types of \"protection\" to improve safety on climbs, creating some of the first \"[[Nut (climbing)|nuts]]\". in 1966 he opened a shop, since expanded to three shops in Snowdonia. He is also remembered for televised rock climbs in the 1960s and was involved in many films.\n\nHe has been appointed a [[Member of the Order of the British Empire]] (MBE) and in 2011 a [[Commander of the Order of the British Empire]] (CBE) in the New Year Honours.\n\n==Biography==\nBorn the seventh and last child of a family in [[Ardwick]], [[Manchester]], [[Lancashire]], England.<ref>\"Joe Brown Biography.\" /</ref> Brown was the first in his family to climb: aged 12, he began exploring from camp sites with his friends. They used discarded clothes lines that were not fit for purpose. Brown was employed by a company called Archies, where he was apprenticed to a plumber and general builder.<ref name=\"Joe Brown Biography 2012\">[https://web.archive.org/web/20120512003631/http://www.joe-brown.com/docman/joe-brown/joe-browns-biography/download.html \"Joe Brown Biography\"] Joe-Brown.com.</ref> He became famous for climbing during the 1950s, and was a member of the Valkyrie Climbing Club and founding member of the [[Rock and Ice climbing club]].<ref name=\"Thompson 2010\">{{cite book|last=Thompson|first=Simon|title=Unjustifiable Risk?|year=2010|publisher=Cicerone|pages=207\u2013209}}</ref> An early climbing partner was [[Don Whillans]], from the neighbouring city of [[County Borough of Salford|Salford]]. They were among the first of a new breed of post-war climbers from working-class backgrounds, in contrast to the upper and middle class professionals who had dominated the sport up to the [[Second World War]].\n\nBrown was enlisted in 1949-50 for 18 months in the [[Royal Army Ordnance Corps]], where he spent his free time climbing with friends. Brown broke his leg in three places in a scrum for the tea urn but was back up and climbing three months later.<ref name=\"Joe Brown Biography 2012\" />\n\nHe established a number of new routes in [[Snowdonia]] and the [[Peak District]] that were at the leading edge of the hardest grades. Examples on [[Dinas Cromlech]] in the [[Llanberis Pass]] include \"Cenotaph Corner\" (1952, graded E1, with Doug Belshaw) and \"Cemetery Gates\" (1951, E1, with Don Whillans).<ref name=\"Thompson 2010\" /> As well as creating pioneering routes, he helped create new types of \"protection\" to improve safety on climbs, and is acknowledged to have created some of the first \"[[Nut (climbing)|nuts]]\" by drilling the thread out of nuts and threading the centre with a sling. So famous was he that the [[Post Office]] would often deliver letters simply addressed to \"The Human Fly, UK\".{{citation needed|date=September 2013}}\n\nBrown's mountaineering achievements in the [[Alps]] and [[Himalayas]]: he made many ascents in the Alps in the 1950s with Whillans and other members of the Rock and Ice climbing club and, in 1955, the first ascent of the world's third highest mountain, [[Kangchenjunga]] in the [[Nepal]]ese [[Himalaya]], with [[George Band]]. In 1956 he made the first ascent of the west summit of the [[Muztagh Tower]] in the [[Karakoram]] with [[Ian McNaught-Davis]]. The other members of the team, John Hartog and [[Tom Patey]], reached the main summit the next day.\n\nApart from numerous rock climbs in Britain, and mountaineering achievements abroad, Brown is remembered for televised rock climbs in the 1960s, three in Snowdonia, and in 1967, a spectacular new route on the [[Old Man of Hoy]], a Scottish [[sea stack]], with Ian McNaught-Davis and [[Chris Bonington]]. Fifteen years later Brown repeated the climb on the Old Man on a television documentary with his second daughter Zoe. Her bubbly personality led her to being chosen as a presenter on the children's TV show ''[[Razzamatazz]]''.<!--Not [[Tiswas]], which had been axed by then-->\n\nAlready a [[Member of the Order of the British Empire]] (MBE), Brown was appointed [[Commander of the Order of the British Empire]] (CBE) in the 2011 New Year Honours for services to rock climbing and mountaineering.<ref>{{London Gazette |issue=59647 |date=31 December 2010 |page=7 |supp=y}}</ref>\n\n[[File:Joe Brown's Shop - geograph.org.uk - 1452330.jpg|thumb|right|Joe Brown shop in [[Capel Curig]]]]\nOn 17 February 1957 Brown married Valerie Melville Gray.\n\nThroughout his climbing career Brown was involved in films such as ''Hazard'',<ref>{{cite web|title=HAZARD (1959) film no: 4570|url=http://www.yorkshirefilmarchive.com/film/hazard|website=Yorkshire Film Archive|accessdate=23 September 2014}}</ref> ''Upsidedown Wales'', ''[[Five Days One Summer]]'', in which he and other British climbers assisted with the mountaineering scenes.\n\nHis first daughter Helen was born in 1960 followed six years later by Zoe. She later repeated a climb for a TV show.\n\nBrown started to create and improve climbing gear and in 1966 opened a shop,<ref name=\"Joe Brown Biography 2012\"/> since expanded to three shops in [[Snowdonia]] and an online presence, branded in English as \"Joe Brown shops\" and in Welsh as \"Siopau Joe Brown\".\n\n==Bibliography==\n*{{cite book  | last = Brown  | first = Joe  | title = The Hard Years  | publisher=Victor Gollancz  | year = 1967\n  | location = London, UK  | url =  | id = \n  | asin = B001PQCRYK }} (Original Hardcover)\n* {{cite book  | last = Brown  | first = Joe  | title = The Hard Years  | publisher=Mountaineers Books  | year = 2001\n  | location = Seattle, WA, USA  | url =  | id = \n  | isbn = 978-0-89886-845-6 }} (Reprint Edition)\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20120511235426/http://www.joe-brown.com/first-ascents/index.php List of Brown's first ascents]\n* [http://wn.com/joe_brown_(climber)/#/Video%20on%20climbing%20the%20kangchenjunga/ Video of an interview with Brown]\n* [http://vimeo.com/7285270 Short clip of Brown in George Smiths film ''Upside Down Wales'']\n* [http://www.joe-brown.com/ Brown's on-line store Joe-Brown.com]\n\n{{Mont Blanc massif}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Brown, Joe}}\n[[Category:1930 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:British rock climbers]]\n[[Category:English mountain climbers]]\n[[Category:Commanders of the Order of the British Empire]]\n[[Category:People from Ardwick]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use British English|date=August 2011}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=August 2011}}\n[[File:Joe Brown.jpg|thumb|right|200px|Brown in the 1990s]]\n'''Joseph Brown''', usually '''Joe Brown''', {{post-nominals|country=GBR|size=100%|commas=on|CBE}} (26 September 1930 - 16 April 2020) is an English [[Climbing|climber]]. He is regarded as the outstanding pioneering English rock climber of the 1950s and early 1960s.\n\nBrown established a number of new routes in [[Snowdonia]] and the [[Peak District]] that were at the leading edge of the hardest grades. He made ascents in the Alps in the 1950s with others and, in 1955, the first ascent of the world's third highest mountain, [[Kangchenjunga]] in the [[Nepal]]ese [[Himalaya]], with [[George Band]]. In 1956 he made the first ascent of the west summit of the [[Muztagh Tower]] in the [[Karakoram]] with [[Ian McNaught-Davis]].\n\nBrown helped create new types of \"protection\" to improve safety on climbs, creating some of the first \"[[Nut (climbing)|nuts]]\". in 1966 he opened a shop, since expanded to three shops in Snowdonia. He is also remembered for televised rock climbs in the 1960s and was involved in many films.\n\nHe has been appointed a [[Member of the Order of the British Empire]] (MBE) and in 2011 a [[Commander of the Order of the British Empire]] (CBE) in the New Year Honours.\n\n==Biography==\nBorn the seventh and last child of a family in [[Ardwick]], [[Manchester]], [[Lancashire]], England.<ref>\"Joe Brown Biography.\" /</ref> Brown was the first in his family to climb: aged 12, he began exploring from camp sites with his friends. They used discarded clothes lines that were not fit for purpose. Brown was employed by a company called Archies, where he was apprenticed to a plumber and general builder.<ref name=\"Joe Brown Biography 2012\">[https://web.archive.org/web/20120512003631/http://www.joe-brown.com/docman/joe-brown/joe-browns-biography/download.html \"Joe Brown Biography\"] Joe-Brown.com.</ref> He became famous for climbing during the 1950s, and was a member of the Valkyrie Climbing Club and founding member of the [[Rock and Ice climbing club]].<ref name=\"Thompson 2010\">{{cite book|last=Thompson|first=Simon|title=Unjustifiable Risk?|year=2010|publisher=Cicerone|pages=207\u2013209}}</ref> An early climbing partner was [[Don Whillans]], from the neighbouring city of [[County Borough of Salford|Salford]]. They were among the first of a new breed of post-war climbers from working-class backgrounds, in contrast to the upper and middle class professionals who had dominated the sport up to the [[Second World War]].\n\nBrown was enlisted in 1949-50 for 18 months in the [[Royal Army Ordnance Corps]], where he spent his free time climbing with friends. Brown broke his leg in three places in a scrum for the tea urn but was back up and climbing three months later.<ref name=\"Joe Brown Biography 2012\" />\n\nHe established a number of new routes in [[Snowdonia]] and the [[Peak District]] that were at the leading edge of the hardest grades. Examples on [[Dinas Cromlech]] in the [[Llanberis Pass]] include \"Cenotaph Corner\" (1952, graded E1, with Doug Belshaw) and \"Cemetery Gates\" (1951, E1, with Don Whillans).<ref name=\"Thompson 2010\" /> As well as creating pioneering routes, he helped create new types of \"protection\" to improve safety on climbs, and is acknowledged to have created some of the first \"[[Nut (climbing)|nuts]]\" by drilling the thread out of nuts and threading the centre with a sling. So famous was he that the [[Post Office]] would often deliver letters simply addressed to \"The Human Fly, UK\".{{citation needed|date=September 2013}}\n\nBrown's mountaineering achievements in the [[Alps]] and [[Himalayas]]: he made many ascents in the Alps in the 1950s with Whillans and other members of the Rock and Ice climbing club and, in 1955, the first ascent of the world's third highest mountain, [[Kangchenjunga]] in the [[Nepal]]ese [[Himalaya]], with [[George Band]]. In 1956 he made the first ascent of the west summit of the [[Muztagh Tower]] in the [[Karakoram]] with [[Ian McNaught-Davis]]. The other members of the team, John Hartog and [[Tom Patey]], reached the main summit the next day.\n\nApart from numerous rock climbs in Britain, and mountaineering achievements abroad, Brown is remembered for televised rock climbs in the 1960s, three in Snowdonia, and in 1967, a spectacular new route on the [[Old Man of Hoy]], a Scottish [[sea stack]], with Ian McNaught-Davis and [[Chris Bonington]]. Fifteen years later Brown repeated the climb on the Old Man on a television documentary with his second daughter Zoe. Her bubbly personality led her to being chosen as a presenter on the children's TV show ''[[Razzamatazz]]''.<!--Not [[Tiswas]], which had been axed by then-->\n\nAlready a [[Member of the Order of the British Empire]] (MBE), Brown was appointed [[Commander of the Order of the British Empire]] (CBE) in the 2011 New Year Honours for services to rock climbing and mountaineering.<ref>{{London Gazette |issue=59647 |date=31 December 2010 |page=7 |supp=y}}</ref>\n\n[[File:Joe Brown's Shop - geograph.org.uk - 1452330.jpg|thumb|right|Joe Brown shop in [[Capel Curig]]]]\nOn 17 February 1957 Brown married Valerie Melville Gray.\n\nThroughout his climbing career Brown was involved in films such as ''Hazard'',<ref>{{cite web|title=HAZARD (1959) film no: 4570|url=http://www.yorkshirefilmarchive.com/film/hazard|website=Yorkshire Film Archive|accessdate=23 September 2014}}</ref> ''Upsidedown Wales'', ''[[Five Days One Summer]]'', in which he and other British climbers assisted with the mountaineering scenes.\n\nHis first daughter Helen was born in 1960 followed six years later by Zoe. She later repeated a climb for a TV show.\n\nBrown started to create and improve climbing gear and in 1966 opened a shop,<ref name=\"Joe Brown Biography 2012\"/> since expanded to three shops in [[Snowdonia]] and an online presence, branded in English as \"Joe Brown shops\" and in Welsh as \"Siopau Joe Brown\".\n\n==Bibliography==\n*{{cite book  | last = Brown  | first = Joe  | title = The Hard Years  | publisher=Victor Gollancz  | year = 1967\n  | location = London, UK  | url =  | id = \n  | asin = B001PQCRYK }} (Original Hardcover)\n* {{cite book  | last = Brown  | first = Joe  | title = The Hard Years  | publisher=Mountaineers Books  | year = 2001\n  | location = Seattle, WA, USA  | url =  | id = \n  | isbn = 978-0-89886-845-6 }} (Reprint Edition)\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20120511235426/http://www.joe-brown.com/first-ascents/index.php List of Brown's first ascents]\n* [ht