at-year = 2019\n| stat1-header = Passengers\n| stat1-data = 12,662,055 <br/> {{increase}} 11.29%\n| stat2-header = Aircraft movements\n| stat2-data = 107,794<br/> {{increase}} 7%\n| stat3-header = Cargo (in kg)\n| stat3-data = 76,570,966<br/> {{decrease}} 6.69%\n| footnotes = Source: MCIAA<ref name=mciaaytd>{{cite web |url=http://mciaa.gov.ph/index.php/statistics/ |author=Department of Transportation - Mactan-Cebu International Airport Authority |website=Mactan-Cebu International Airport Authority |title=Passengers 2017 |accessdate=11 February 2018}}</ref>\n}}\n'''Mactan\u2013Cebu International Airport''' ({{lang-ceb|Tugpahanang Pangkalibutan sa Mactan\u2013Sugbo}}, {{lang-tgl|Paliparang Pandaigdig ng Mactan\u2013Cebu}}) {{Airport codes|CEB|RPVM}} is the second busiest [[international airport]] in the [[Philippines]].<ref>{{cite book|author=Hoontrakul, P.|title=The Global Rise of Asian Transformation: Trends and Developments in Economic Growth Dynamics|date=2014|publisher=Palgrave Macmillan|location=New York}}</ref> It is located in [[Lapu-Lapu, Philippines|Lapu-Lapu City]] on [[Mactan Island]], a part of [[Metro Cebu]] and serves the [[Central Visayas]] region. The airport is managed by the Mactan\u2013Cebu International Airport Authority and is hub of [[Cebu Pacific]], [[Pan Pacific Airlines]], and [[Royal Air Charter Service]].\n\nOn {{convert|797|ha}}, it has a single {{convert|3300|m|sp=us|adj=on}} runway that was built by the [[United States]] in 1956 as an emergency airport for U.S. Air Forces' [[Strategic Air Command]] bombers and was known as the [[Mactan Air Base]].<ref name=GlobalSecurity />  The runway is complemented by a full-length taxiway that it shares with the current [[Mactan Air Base]] of the [[Philippine Air Force]].\n\n==History==\nThe runway was built by the [[United States Air Force]] in 1956 as an emergency airport for [[Strategic Air Command]] bombers and it was known as the [[Mactan Air Base]].<ref name=GlobalSecurity>{{cite web|title=Mactan\u2013Benito Ebuen Air Base|url=http://www.globalsecurity.org/military/world/philippines/ebuen.htm|publisher=Globalsecurity.org|accessdate=July 22, 2013}}</ref> It remained a spartan outpost until the [[Vietnam War]] in the 1960s when it became a base for a [[C-130]] unit of the U.S. Air Force.<ref name=GlobalSecurity />\n\nIn the mid-1960s, the civilian airport was opened, to replace the now closed [[Lahug Airport]] (now the site of [[Cebu IT Park]]), which could no longer be expanded due to safety and physical problems. The airport was later expanded to the current Mactan\u2013Cebu International Airport (MCIA).\n\nOn August 20, 2008, the Mactan\u2013Cebu International Airport Authority (MCIAA) announced that about 300 million Philippine pesos will be spent for the terminal expansion program to address the increasing volume of passenger traffic. MCIAA former general manager Danilo Augusto Francia said the program also includes the establishment of a second passenger terminal in the Mactan\u2013Cebu International Airport.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://globalnation.inquirer.net/cebudailynews/enterprise/view/20080820-155792/Mactan-Cebu-airport-to-set-aside-P300-M-for-expansion|title=Mactan\u2013Cebu airport to set aside P300-M for expansion|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080916223549/http://globalnation.inquirer.net/cebudailynews/enterprise/view/20080820-155792/Mactan-Cebu-airport-to-set-aside-P300-M-for-expansion |archivedate=September 16, 2008|website=globalnation.inquirer.net|url-status=unfit }}</ref>  In 2009, former general manager Francia announced for the public bidding for the construction of the new generation terminal to service only international flights.\n\nIn 2010, the newly elected Philippine President, [[Benigno Aquino III]] selected [[Nigel Paul Villarete]] as the new General Manager of the Mactan\u2013Cebu International Airport (MCIA)<ref>{{cite web|website=Positive News Media|title=P-Noy names four Cebuanos to Mactan airport board|url=http://www.allvoices.com/s/event-6803478/aHR0cDovL3Bvc2l0aXZlbmV3c21lZGlhLm5ldC9hbTIvcHVibGlzaC9CdXNpbmVzc18xOS9QLU5veV9uYW1lc19mb3VyX0NlYnVhbm9zX3RvX01hY3Rhbl9haXJwb3J0X2JvYXJkLnNodG1s |accessdate=2011-01-31 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120328113923/http://www.allvoices.com/s/event-6803478/aHR0cDovL3Bvc2l0aXZlbmV3c21lZGlhLm5ldC9hbTIvcHVibGlzaC9CdXNpbmVzc18xOS9QLU5veV9uYW1lc19mb3VyX0NlYnVhbm9zX3RvX01hY3Rhbl9haXJwb3J0X2JvYXJkLnNodG1s |archivedate=March 28, 2012 |df=mdy-all }}</ref> and Chief Executive Officer (CEO) of MCIAA.  Mr. Villarete prioritized the completion of the terminal expansion<ref>{{cite news|website=www.passengerterminaltoday.com|title=Expanded Mactan\u2013Cebu to open in November|url=http://www.passengerterminaltoday.com/news.php?NewsID=27172|access-date=January 31, 2011|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110715051520/http://www.passengerterminaltoday.com/news.php?NewsID=27172|archive-date=July 15, 2011|url-status=dead}}</ref> and the completion of the unfinished administration building.<ref>{{cite web|first=Gregg M.|last=Rubio|date=November 3, 2010 |website=Philippine Star|title=Villarete to finish MCIAA administrative building despite corruption tag|url=http://www.philstar.com/Article.aspx?articleId=626707&publicationSubCategoryId=107}}{{dead link|date=September 2019}}</ref>\n\nFollowing [[Typhoon Haiyan|Typhoon Haiyan (Yolanda)]], one of the biggest typhoons ever recorded and one of the most destructive [[typhoons in the Philippines]], the airport was used as a center for air operations for the relief effort.  The airport is centrally located in the [[Visayas]] which was the region most affected by the storm, especially the [[Eastern Visayas]] islands of [[Leyte]] and [[Samar]].  The Cebu airport was relatively unaffected by the storm while the airports of  the Eastern Visayas were unusable immediately after.\n\nOn November 12, 2013, the world's longest and heaviest aircraft, the [[Antonov An-225 Mriya|Antonov An-225 ''Mriya'']], landed at MCIA from the [[Zagreb International Airport]] in [[Croatia]] for the first time in the Philippines to deliver a 180-ton replacement transformer from the Croatian energy company [[KON\u010cAR Group|KON\u010cAR]] to the [[First Philippine Holdings Corporation|First Gen Corporation]]'s power plant in [[Batangas City]]. Officials of First Gen approached MCIAA General Manager Nigel Paul Villarete to allow the Antonov An-225 to utilize the airport for the transportation of their delivery after officials from [[Clark International Airport]], the [[Ninoy Aquino International Airport]] in [[Manila]], and [[Subic Bay International Airport]] refused to allow the aircraft to utilize their airports.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Alegado|first1=Sieg|title=World's biggest plane to deliver 140-ton power generator to PHL|url=http://www.gmanetwork.com/news/story/334989/scitech/technology/world-s-biggest-plane-to-deliver-140-ton-power-generator-to-phl|accessdate=December 21, 2015|work=[[GMA News Online]]|publisher=[[GMA Network Inc.]]|date=November 12, 2013}}</ref> According to First Gen President Francis Giles Puno, MCIA had been inspected by [[Antonov Airlines]], the owner of the Antonov An-225 aircraft, as the most viable option for their aircraft, \"after considering the combination of airport, onward land transport and sea freight.\"<ref>{{cite news|last1=Sollane|first1=Jose|title=World\u2019s biggest airplane in Cebu|url=http://www.philstar.com/cebu-news/2013/11/13/1256104/worlds-biggest-airplane-cebu|accessdate=December 21, 2015|work=[[The Freeman (newspaper)|The Freeman]]|publisher=[[The Philippine Star|PhilStar Daily, Inc.]]|date=November 13, 2013}}</ref>\n\nOn April 23, 2014, the Department of Transportation and Communications awarded the operations and maintenance of MCIA to a consortium of the Philippine [[Megawide Construction Corporation]] and [[Bangalore]]-based [[GMR Group|GMR Infrastructure]]. The consortium won with a bid of {{Philippine peso|17.5 billion}}. MCIAA handed over the operations and maintenance of the airport to the private consortium on November 1, 2014.<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.philstar.com/business/2014/04/23/1314907/megawide-gmr-remits-p161-b-payment-cebu-airport-project |title=Megawide-GMR remits P16.1-B payment for Cebu airport project |last=Agcaoili |first=Lawrence |date=April 23, 2014 |work=Philstar.com}}</ref> In the first half of 2016, MCIA and GMCAC started the rehabilitation, renovation and expansion of Terminal 1 as Phase 1 of the project. The new terminal building was designed by Integrated Design Associates Ltd. (IDA)<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.mb.com.ph/megawide-gmr-airport-design-reflects-cebu-culture/# |title=Archived copy |access-date=May 17, 2014 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140517234806/http://www.mb.com.ph/megawide-gmr-airport-design-reflects-cebu-culture/# |archive-date=May 17, 2014 |url-status=dead |df=mdy-all }}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |url=http://asia.nikkei.com/Business/Business-Briefs/PhilippineIndia-consortium-to-overhaul-Cebu-airport-by-2018# |title=Archived copy |access-date=May 17, 2014 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140520063329/http://asia.nikkei.com/Business/Business-Briefs/PhilippineIndia-consortium-to-overhaul-Cebu-airport-by-2018# |archive-date=May 20, 2014 |url-status=dead |df=mdy-all }}</ref> On January 25, 2018, GMR\u2013Megawide Cebu Airport Corporation (GMCAC) chief executive advisor Andrew Acquaah-Harrison announced that the new terminal building would be the MCIA Terminal 2<ref>{{cite news|last1=Bunachita|first1=Jose Santino|title=New Mactan Cebu Airport terminal seen to open ahead of schedule|url=http://newsinfo.inquirer.net/963557/new-mactan-cebu-airport-terminal-seen-to-open-ahead-of-schedule|accessdate=February 27, 2018|work=Philippine Daily Inquirer|date=January 25, 2018}}</ref> will start operations on July 1, 2018 and cater to international flights.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Lopez|first1=Virgil|title=Duterte inaugurates new \u2018resort-like\u2019 Mactan Cebu airport terminal|url=http://www.gmanetwork.com/news/news/nation/656069/duterte-inaugurates-new-resort-like-mactan-cebu-airport-terminal|accessdate=June 7, 2018|work=GMA News|date=June 7, 2018}}</ref>\n\nOn July 29, 2015, President Benigno Aquino III led the ground-breaking rites at the site of the old Philippine Air Force base in Lapu-Lapu City which had been demolished to pave way for the Terminal 2 construction.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://cnnphilippines.com/regional/2015/06/29/president-aquino-breaks-ground-mactan-cebu-airport-terminal-2.html|title=Aquino breaks ground on P32B Cebu airport terminal project|work=CNN Philippines|access-date=2015-06-29|language=en-US}}</ref> On June 7, 2018, Terminal 2 was inaugurated by President [[Rodrigo Duterte]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.gmanetwork.com/news/news/nation/656069/duterte-inaugurates-new-resort-like-mactan-cebu-airport-terminal/story/|title=Duterte inaugurates new \u2018resort-like\u2019 Mactan Cebu airport terminal|work=GMA News Online|access-date=2018-06-07|language=en-US}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=http://newsinfo.inquirer.net/998653/duterte-leads-inauguration-of-new-mactan-airport-passenger-terminal|title=Duterte leads inauguration of new Mactan airport passenger terminal|last=Bunachita|first=Jose Santino|access-date=June 7, 2018|language=en}}</ref> On August 27, 2018, which is also National Heroes Day in the Philippines, President Duterte expressed support for renaming the airport after Mactan chieftain [[Lapu-Lapu]] whose forces killed [[Ferdinand Magellan]] during the [[Battle of Mactan]] in 1521.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.philstar.com/business/2018/08/27/1846287/duterte-favors-renaming-mactan-airport-cebu-after-lapu-lapu|title=Duterte favors renaming Mactan airport in Cebu after Lapu-Lapu|last=Adel|first=Rosette|date=August 27, 2018|work=[[The Philippine STAR]]|access-date=August 28, 2018|language=en}}</ref>\n\nOn June 4, 2019, an [[Airbus A350|A350-1000]], the most advanced aircraft of [[Airbus]], landed at MCIA for the first time as the [[Cathay Pacific]] airliner to be used primarily along with the [[A330|A330-300]] for Hong Kong-Cebu and Cebu-Hong Kong flights.\n\nIn 2020, the second runway of the airport will begin its construction so that planes could land at the airport simultaneously.\n\n==Future development==\nOn 22 May 2017, Mactan\u2013Cebu International Airport Authority (MCIAA) passed a resolution approving the proposal to start the construction of a second runway, which was proposed by Rep. Raul Del Mar of Cebu. Del Mar proposed that the construction of the second runway be funded using P4.9- billion sourced from the P14.4 billion premium given by the GMCAC when it won the bid to develop and manage the MCIA terminal. Once completed, the second runway will be adjacent to the existing first runway and will enable simultaneous runway operations.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.sunstar.com.ph/cebu/local-news/2017/05/21/2nd-runway-project-go-543138|title=2nd runway project a 'go'|first=Rona Joyce T.|last=Fernandez|date=May 21, 2017|publisher=}}</ref>\n\n== Terminals ==\n[[File:President Rodrigo Roa Duterte takes a tour inside the Mactan-Cebu-International Airport (MCIA) Terminal 2.jpg|230px|thumb|right|President Rodrigo Duterte takes a tour inside the newly inaugurated MCIA Terminal 2 in 2018]]\n\n=== Terminal 1 (Domestic) ===\nTerminal 1, which was built in 1990, serves as the airport's domestic terminal. Prior to the completion and opening of Terminal 2, it housed both domestic and international operations and has an annual capacity of 4.5 million passengers. By the end of 2017, it served more than 10 million passengers.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://ppp.gov.ph/?p=7469# |title=Archived copy |access-date=May 19, 2013 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130807155704/http://ppp.gov.ph/?p=7469# |archive-date=August 7, 2013 |url-status=dead |df=mdy-all }}</ref>\n\nThe terminal has six boarding bridges and also has remote parking spaces for aircraft.\n\n=== Terminal 2 (International) ===\nTerminal 2, which started construction in 2016 and opened for operations on July 1, 2018, is the newest airport terminal and has increased the capacity of the airport to 12.5 million passengers per year.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://businessmirror.com.ph/megawide-to-open-mactan-cebu-airport-terminal-2-in-june/|title=Megawide to open Mactan-Cebu airport Terminal 2 in June|work=BusinessMirror|access-date=2018-07-04|language=en-US}}</ref> It currently handles all international flights. The design of the terminal has timber arches that look like an inverted boat hull, and a wave-like roof that evokes a tropical and resort-like feel. It represents the sea waves that surrounds the island of [[Cebu]]. The international terminal won an award for the category \"Completed Buildings - Transport\" at the World Architecture Festival in 2019.<ref>{{cite web |title=Completed Buildings Transport winner |url=https://www.worldarchitecturefestival.com/node/3495 |website=World Architecture Festival |publisher=World Architecture Festival |accessdate=7 December 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title=Mactan Cebu International Airport wins World Architecture award |url=https://news.abs-cbn.com/business/12/05/19/mactan-cebu-international-airport-wins-world-architecture-award |accessdate=7 December 2019 |agency=ABS-CBN |publisher=ABS-CBN News |date=5 December 2019}}</ref>\n\nThe new terminal building has five boarding bridges, two of which are expandable, thus making a total of seven boarding bridges.\n\n==Airlines and destinations==\n\n[[File:First UK-funded humanitarian flight arrives in Cebu, Philippines - 10826427444.jpg|thumbnail|right|A [[Boeing 777F]] operated by [[Emirates SkyCargo]] at the airport with relief goods for Typhoon Haiyan/Yolanda donated by the [[United Kingdom]]'s [[Department for International Development]]]]The airport flies to 36 domestic destinations and 37 international ones.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://mciaa.gov.ph/data-sheet/|title=DATA SHEET \u2013 Mactan \u2013 Cebu International Airport Authority}}</ref>[[File:RP-C3249 Airbus A320 Cebu Pacific (7838610022).jpg|thumb|right|[[Cebu Pacific]]'s [[A320-200]] taxiing.]]\n[[File:Philippine Airlines Airbus A330-300 MRD-1.jpg|thumb|[[Philippine Airlines]]' [[A330-300]] landing.]]\n[[File:9V-SLI Airbus A320 Silk Air (7838487654).jpg|thumb|[[SilkAir]]'s [[A320-200]] landing.]]\n\n===Passenger===\n{{Airport-dest-list\n<!-- -->\n|[[Air Busan]]|[[Gimhae International Airport|Busan]], [[Incheon International Airport|Seoul\u2013Incheon]]\n<!-- -->                                                                                                                                 \n|[[Air Juan]]|[[Bantayan Airport|Bantayan]], [[Catbalogan Airport|Catbalogan]], [[Panan-awan Airport|Maasin]], [[Biliran Airport|Naval]], [[Sipalay Airport|Sipalay]], [[Siquijor Airport|Siquijor]], [[Bohol\u2013Panglao International Airport|Tagbilaran]]<ref name=\"CEB_Ban_20\"/>\n<!-- -->\n|[[AirSWIFT]]|[[El Nido Airport|El Nido]]<ref name=\"CEB_Ban_20\"/>\n<!-- -->\n|[[Asiana Airlines]]|[[Incheon International Airport|Seoul\u2013Incheon]]\n<!-- -->\n|[[Cathay Pacific]]|[[Hong Kong International Airport|Hong Kong]]\n<!-- -->\n|[[Cebu Pacific]]|[[Laguindingan International Airport|Cagayan de Oro]],<ref name=\"gma\"/> [[Godofredo P. Ramos Airport|Caticlan]],<ref name=\"CEB_Ban_20\"/> [[Clark International Airport|Clark]],<ref name=\"gma\"/> [[Awang Airport|Cotabato]],<ref name=\"CEB_Ban_20\"/> [[Francisco Bangoy International Airport|Davao]],<ref name=\"CEB_Ban_20\"/> [[General Santos International Airport|General Santos]],<ref name=\"CEB_Ban_20\"/> [[Hong Kong International Airport|Hong Kong]], [[Iloilo International Airport|Iloilo]],<ref name=\"CEB_Ban_20\"/> [[Kalibo International Airport|Kalibo]],<ref name=\"CEB_Ban_20\"/> [[Macau International Airport|Macau]], [[Ninoy Aquino International Airport|Manila]],<ref name=\"CEB_Ban_20\"/> [[Puerto Princesa International Airport|Puerto Princesa]],<ref name=\"CEB_Ban_20\"/> [[Incheon International Airport|Seoul\u2013Incheon]], [[Shanghai Pudong International Airport|Shanghai\u2013Pudong]], [[Singapore Changi Airport|Singapore]], [[Narita International Airport|Tokyo\u2013Narita]], [[Zamboanga International Airport|Zamboanga]]<ref name=\"CEB_Ban_20\"/>\n<!-- -->\n|[[Cebu Pacific]]<br>{{nowrap|operated by [[Cebgo]]}}|[[Bacolod\u2013Silay Airport|Bacolod]],<ref name=\"CEB_Ban_20\" /> [[Francisco B. Reyes Airport|Busuanga]] ,<ref name=\"CEB_Ban_20\" /> [[Bancasi Airport|Butuan]],<ref name=\"CEB_Ban_20\" /> [[Laguindingan International Airport|Cagayan de Oro]],<ref name=\"gma\"/> [[Calbayog Airport|Calbayog]],<ref name=\"CEB_Ban_20\"/> [[Camiguin Airport|Camiguin]]<ref name=\"CEB_Ban_20\"/>, [[Godofredo P. Ramos Airport|Caticlan]] ,<ref name=\"CEB_Ban_20\"/> [[Dipolog Airport|Dipolog]],<ref name=\"CEB_Ban_20\"/> [[Sibulan Airport|Dumaguete]],<ref name=\"gma\"/> [[Iloilo International Airport|Iloilo]],<ref name=\"CEB_Ban_20\" /> [[Legazpi Airport|Legazpi]],<ref name=\"CEB_Ban_20\"/> [[Ninoy Aquino International Airport|Manila]],<ref name=\"CEB_Ban_20\" /> [[Labo Airport|Ozamiz]],<ref name=\"CEB_Ban_20\" /> [[Pagadian Airport|Pagadian]],<ref name=\"CEB_Ban_20\" /> [[Sayak Airport|Siargao]] ,<ref name=\"CEB_Ban_20\" /> [[Surigao Airport|Surigao]],<ref name=\"CEB_Ban_20\"/> [[Daniel Z. Romualdez Airport|Tacloban]],<ref name=\"CEB_Ban_20\"/> [[Zamboanga International Airport|Zamboanga]]<ref name=\"CEB_Ban_20\"/>\n<!-- -->\n|[[China Airlines]]|[[Taoyuan International Airport|Taipei\u2013Taoyuan]] (resumes 12 June 2020)<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://focustaiwan.tw/news/asoc/201912050014.aspx|title=CAL to launch regular flights to Cebu from March|website=focustaiwan.tw}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |last1=Liu |first1=Jim |title=China Airlines / Mandarin Airlines Feb/Mar 2020 Service adjustment as of 05MAR20 |url=https://www.routesonline.com/news/38/airlineroute/290106/china-airlines